<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-07 00:21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Report: Top NKorea Violinist Defects  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEOUL, South Korea (AP) -- South Korea's intelligence agency on
Thursday identified a top North Korean violinist who fled his
communist homeland.
</P>
<P>
   The violinist's defection had been made public last year, it
said.
</P>
<P>
   On July 30, 1999, Seoul's Foreign Ministry said that two North
Koreans including a 37-year-old artist, identified as Kim Moon
Seok, sought asylum in South Korea.
</P>
<P>
   South Korea's national news agency, Yonhap, said Wednesday that
a member of North Korea's national orchestra, identified as Kim
Young Wook, 38, defected to South Korea last July.
</P>
<P>
   Kim Moon Seok and Kim Young Wook are the same person, the
intelligence agency said.
</P>
<P>
   South Korean intelligence usually uses pseudonyms to identify
important North Korean defectors in an effort to protect their
families in their Stalinist homeland.
</P>
<P>
   Yonhap reported that Kim's 36-year-old wife Chang Myung Hwa and
their 8-year-old daughter were also in South Korea.
</P>
<P>
   The intelligence service declined to release any information
about Kim's family, including their whereabouts.
</P>
<P>
   Kim fled his communist homeland in 1996 and defected to South
Korea a year later via a third country, the Foreign Ministry said
last year.
</P>
<P>
   About 400 North Koreans have defected to South Korea in the past
five years. Most have complained about food shortages in the
isolated country.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-09-07-00 0021 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
