<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-07 01:03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Delta decides to scrap Portland-to-Japan flights  </HEADLINE>
By JOSEPH B. FRAZIER
<TEXT>
<P>
   PORTLAND, Ore. (AP) - Stung by low ridership and high operating
costs, Delta Air Lines said Wednesday it will discontinue its last
two direct flights from Portland to Japan starting next April -
ending 13 years of service.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's a very difficult, but very necessary business decision,''
said Mac Armstrong, executive vice president of operations for
Delta.
</P>
<P>
   Delta plans to replace its Portland-Japan service with one daily
round-trip flight to Tokyo from New York's John F. Kennedy airport
and one daily round-trip flight to Nagoya, Japan from Los Angeles.
Delta will also ground the domestic flights that feed the Japan
routes, including a flight between Portland and New York.
</P>
<P>
   Armstrong said the airline has lost $10 million on the
Portland-Japan routes in the past 12 months.
</P>
<P>
   ''We looked at every possible business option to return the
flights to profitability,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Armstrong said problems with the U.S. Immigration and
Naturalization Service, which has been criticized for detaining and
deporting a disproportionately large number of foreign visitors at
Portland airport, were ''not an economic factor in our decision.''
</P>
<P>
   But he seemed to acknowledge that Portland airport's reputation
in Asia - where some call it ''Deportland'' - may have scared off
some travelers.
</P>
<P>
   ''I would comment that the situation certainly was a factor from
a customer service point of view,'' he said without elaboration.
</P>
<P>
   Toyojiro Soejima, Japan's consul-general to Portland, seemed to
put more blame on the INS.
</P>
<P>
   ''We cannot deny the negative influence on the travelers coming
to Portland for either business or pleasure,'' he said. ''The
question is how big a factor it was with Delta.''
</P>
<P>
   He called Delta's decision ''unfortunate'' and ''more than a
little disappointing''
</P>
<P>
   Even if INS' inspectors' reputation for rigidity in dealing with
foreigners at Portland airport had no role in Delta's decision, an
aviation analyst said the airport could lose even more prestige
with Delta scrapping the flights to and from Japan.
</P>
<P>
   ''The main thing it does is give a status blow to Portland and
Delta,'' said Terry Trippler, an airline specialist at
OneTravel.Com in Minneapolis.
</P>
<P>
   Oregon officials worried about the possible impact of Delta's
decision on economic ties between the state and Asia.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're saddened by this,'' said Todd Davidson, director of the
Oregon Tourism Commission. ''Folks have been working hard for 20
years to get nonstop service. This means we'll have to work
harder.''
</P>
<P>
   Bill Scott, director of economic and community development for
Oregon, called it ''a real setback for our developing trade
relationships'' because the flights were bringing Oregon a
significant number of tourist dollars.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. John Kitzhaber said, ''I wish Delta were making a different
announcement today, but I understand and respect the business
decision they had to make and the competitive pressures that forced
them to make it.
</P>
<P>
   ''Oregon's connections with Asia predate this direct service,
and our relationship with Asia will survive its cancellation,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Oregon authorities had urged Delta not to scrap its flights
between Portland and Japan, and had been prepared to offer up to $5
million in incentives to stay. However, Delta has calculated it
could save some $40 million by leaving.
</P>
<P>
   Patterns of flights to Asia have changed fundamentally in the
past few years as a result of the 1997 U.S.-Japan bilateral
agreement, ''reducing the viability of our gateway in Portland,''
said Leo F. Mullin, Delta chairman and chief executive officer.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement allows nonstop flights to Japan from interior
airports such as Chicago and New York.
</P>
<P>
   ''Passenger traffic through Portland had dropped. And there's
not enough local traffic from the Portland area to make up the
shortfall,'' Armstrong said.
</P>
<P>
   He said the economic crisis in Japan in recent years added to
the problem.
</P>
<P>
   Mullin said capacity to Japan has increased by ''nearly 25
percent, but much of the traffic is being carried nonstop from
interior hubs'' and bypassing the West Coast.
</P>
<P>
   The decision to discontinue the two international flights will
lead to a reduction in domestic flights that supported the
Portland-to-Japan service, the airline said.
</P>
<P>
   As of April 1 Portland's domestic schedule will be reduced from
24 Delta departures serving 12 U.S. markets to 15 departures
serving five markets - Delta's hubs at Atlanta, Cincinnati, Salt
Lake City and Dallas/Fort Worth, and one-stop service via Seattle
to Delta's trans-Atlantic gateway at New York's JFK airport.
</P>
<P>
   The decision means a cut in Delta's job force in the Portland
area. The airline will reduce its Portland-are work force to 870
from 1,200.
</P>
<P>
   ''There will be a job in the Delta system for every
Portland-based Delta employee affected by this transition. If those
jobs are not attractive to all who are affected, we will offer
other options to help in the transition,'' Mullin said.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Gritta, an airline specialist and professor of finance
at the University of Portland, said Portland needs a larger airport
if it wants to be a major player.
</P>
<P>
   He said as skies open over China and Russia, distances will
shorten because flights will be able to take ''great circle''
routes without having to skirt national borders.
</P>
<P>
   While this will shorten distances to Asian destinations from
West Coast cities, it also will shorten them from interior cities,
he said, putting further competition on West Coast airports.
</P>
<P>
   Port Director Thorne said he understood Delta's financial
explanation but was disappointed in a decision that turned its back
on a longtime relationship with the Portland community and its
civic and business leaders.
</P>
<P>
   ''My goal is to find someone else to provide nonstop service,''
he said. ''The quicker we move the better. The longer the void goes
unfilled, the worse it will be.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-09-07-00 0103 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000907.0007 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-07 01:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Fair Trial For Berenson Said Tough  </HEADLINE>
By KEVIN GRAY
<TEXT>
<P>
   LIMA, Peru (AP) -- After meeting with Peruvian judicial
officials, a lawyer for the family of Lori Berenson says it's
unlikely the American woman could receive a fair trial in Peru.
</P>
<P>
   ''We plead for a fair trial for Lori -- if, and only if, it's
found that another trial can be lawfully held, which we do no
believe is possible,'' Ramsey Clark, a longtime legal adviser to
the Berensons, said late Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Berenson, 30, was convicted of treason by a military tribunal in
1996 for allegedly helping a rebel group, the Tupac Amaru
Revolutionary Movement, plot an attack on the Peruvian Congress.
She denies the charges.
</P>
<P>
   Berenson's mother, Rhoda, arrived in Lima with Clark over the
weekend, several days after the government revoked a life sentence
handed down by hooded judges and granted Berenson a new, civilian
trial.
</P>
<P>
   But Clark said the trial, which began Monday, had started while
Berenson still was without legal representation. He said the judge
in the case had begun questioning witnesses and had not allowed the
family access to files detailing the charges or any of the witness
testimony.
</P>
<P>
   ''We have a right to be present when the witnesses are being
examined,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Clark said he was petitioning the judge to suspend the trial
until the family had adequate time to prepare Berenson's defense.
</P>
<P>
   Peruvian President Alberto Fujimori has said Berenson's sentence
was overturned because of new evidence showing Berenson was not a
leader of the rebel group known by its initials MRTA, as she was
charged when convicted of treason four years ago.
</P>
<P>
   In a radio interview taped in March 1999 but aired for the first
time early Wednesday, the New York native declared her innocence,
and also asserted a fair trial was nearly impossible in Peru.
</P>
<P>
   ''With ... such negative publicity that I've had in Peru, I
would never get a fair trial,'' Berenson told Pacifica Radio in an
exclusive interview taped while she was held in the Socbabaya
Prison in southern Peru. Last week, she was moved to a
maximum-security prison in Lima.
</P>
<P>
   She said she is ''innocent of the charges they made against
me.''
</P>
<P>
   Berenson's case is now being examined by a prosecutor and a
judge in closed-door hearings that could last up to 50 days. If
found guilty, Berenson would then appear in an open trial before
the Supreme Court, with the burden of proving her innocence.
</P>
<P>
   A conviction of terrorism by a civilian court carries a minimum
20-year-sentence.
</P>
<P>
   Berenson's parents have led a campaign for her release,
condemning harsh conditions she has lived under in Peruvian prisons
and asserting their daughter was never involved in any rebel group
activities, but was instead in Peru working as a journalist.
</P>
<P>
   After meeting with her daughter Wednesday, the elder Berenson
said she found her in good spirits, and still ''maintaining her
sense of humor.''
</P>
<P>
   She also added: ''She is still maintaining her innocence. She
has never been a member of the MRTA and she has never associated
with any terrorist acts.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-09-07-00 0112 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000907.0008 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-07 01:13 </DATE_TIME>
