<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-07 02:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bush Presses Military Readiness  </HEADLINE>
By LAURIE KELLMAN
<TEXT>
<P>
   DETROIT (AP) -- George W. Bush is getting help from two
well-known military leaders, retired Gens. Colin Powell and Norman
Schwarzkopf, in pressing his argument that the Clinton-Gore
administration has failed to update the military and prepare it for
war.
</P>
<P>
   ''Let's get something straight. These are not criticisms of the
military,'' the Republican presidential nominee said Wednesday at
the American Legion convention in Milwaukee, Wis.
</P>
<P>
   ''They are criticisms of the current commander in chief and the
vice president for not providing the necessary leadership,'' said
Bush, wearing his blue American Legion cap from a post in Houston.
</P>
<P>
   Proving his capability on national defense and diplomacy has
been a key challenge for Bush, who also is convinced that the issue
of military readiness is a weak spot for Democratic rival Al Gore.
</P>
<P>
   So during this week's reprise of his main campaign themes, Bush
is highlighting luminaries who led the nation -- and his father,
President Bush -- through the Cold War and the Persian Gulf War.
</P>
<P>
   With the military figures at his side during campaign stops
Thursday in Michigan and Ohio, Bush was re-emphasizing a key theme:
''Transforming'' the military from an instrument of Cold War-era
conflicts into a more technologically advanced force that can fight
Information Age battles.
</P>
<P>
   ''Now is the time to shape the future of the military with new
concepts, new strategies, new resolves,'' he told the American
Legion. ''We will challenge the status quo and envision a new
architecture for American defense for decades to come. Our forces
... must have the technology to dominate information, as well as
the technology to dominate the skies and the seas in order to keep
the peace.''
</P>
<P>
   Running mate Dick Cheney, the elder Bush's defense secretary,
was to make a similar pitch Thursday in Portland, Maine.
</P>
<P>
   It is a familiar, but not recently emphasized theme for Bush,
who first discussed it a year ago in his first address on national
defense at The Citadel in South Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   He has hammered the administration harder, however, on military
readiness.
</P>
<P>
   But the issue stung him in July when, in his speech accepting
the GOP presidential nomination, he misstated one fact when talking
about Army readiness.
</P>
<P>
   Bush said: ''If called on by the commander in chief today, two
entire divisions of the Army would have to report ... 'Not ready
for duty, sir.'''
</P>
<P>
   He also accuses Gore of proposing to shortchange the armed
forces on funding and benefits. But the vice president's campaign
released an economic plan Wednesday that would spend $100 billion
of the projected budget surplus on the military over 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   Bush would dedicate $45 billion of the surplus over the same
period.
</P>
<P>
   ''Any argument that he comes up with that we are not dedicating
the resources needed for our military men and women is just talk,
pure rhetoric,'' said Kym Spell, a spokeswoman for Gore.
</P>
<P>
   Bush spokesman Ari Fleischer pointed out Gore has lowered
projected military spending since last month when he said he would
spend $128 million over 10 years. He said Bush's $45 billion figure
was not set in stone.
</P>
<P>
   ''The governor has said he is willing to have a top-to-bottom
review upon election to see how we can restore our military to make
it more efficient and more lethal and we will reserve judgment
until that is done,'' said Fleischer.
</P>
<P>
   Powell and Schwarzkopf are among those Bush has said he'd like
on his foreign policy team, along with former secretaries of state
George Shultz and Henry Kissinger.
</P>
<P>
   The military theme comes near the end of a week that had Bush
hopscotching across battleground states in an effort to regain the
campaign momentum stolen by Gore.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-09-07-00 0215 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000907.0026 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-07 02:16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bush Ads Probe Gore Credibility  </HEADLINE>
By LAURA MECKLER
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- George W. Bush's new ad is about debating Al
Gore, but the real message is about his credibility, the second
commercial in two weeks to do so. ''If we can't trust Al Gore on
debates, why should we trust him on anything?'' the ad concludes.
</P>
<P>
   As the campaign for the White House intensifies, the Republican
presidential candidate's upbeat messages are being replaced by
hard-hitting digs at his Democratic opposition.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans in key states welcomed the change in tactics, saying
swing voters care whether Gore is being straight with them. They
also hope the new focus on Gore's credibility will help Bush regain
the lead from Gore.
</P>
<P>
   ''Most campaigns would like to have the luxury of staying
positive, but in order to stay positive you've got to stay
significantly ahead in the polls,'' said Tom Slade, former chairman
of the Florida Republican Party. ''In races that get close -- and
this one obviously has -- the knives are going to come out.''
</P>
<P>
   Portraying Gore as untrustworthy is key to winning support for
Bush, Republicans reason, and he somehow must convince voters they
want a change in times of unprecedented prosperity.
</P>
<P>
   At least one GOP adviser to Bush, however, was concerned he may
be spending too much time using the debates to make that case.
Other Republicans questioned the effectiveness of the latest spot.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm not sure that's an issue that the average voter cares
about,'' said Timothy Jay Houseal, an attorney in Wilmington, Del.,
who is active in Republican politics.
</P>
<P>
   Stephen Hess, who studies politics at the Brookings Institution,
agreed that undecided voters probably don't care about the details
over debates. ''This isn't what they're talking about around the
water fountain today,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   That may explain why Bush's campaign was considering only a
token buy in just a handful of markets. The ad may have been
designed as much for reporters as voters, as Bush tries to
outmaneuver Gore on debate formats and settings.
</P>
<P>
   Bush has accepted only one of three 90-minute prime-time debates
proposed by the bipartisan commission that has run presidential
debates since 1988. Instead, citing offers by Gore to debate him in
dozens of other locations, Bush accepted debate invitations from
NBC and CNN talk shows.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's campaign says Bush must agree to the full set of
commission debates before any others.
</P>
<P>
   Gore suggests Bush is dodging debates that would be seen by
large audiences. Republicans counter that Gore's rejection of
Bush's offer shows he is untrustworthy.
</P>
<P>
   ''When it was politically convenient, Gore said he'd debate
anytime, anyplace, anywhere,'' an announcer says in the new
30-second spot. ''Now that Governor Bush has accepted, Gore says
'unacceptable.'''
</P>
<P>
   The debate ad follows a Republican National Committee
commercial, already airing in 16 states, that questions Gore's
credibility on campaign finance reform and mocks him for claiming a
key role in developing the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Woody Cozad, former Missouri GOP chairman, predicted the
skirmish about debates, though not ideal, will help Bush because
the earlier RNC ad already has laid the ground work.
</P>
<P>
   ''You already have a message on the air that Gore is in fact
unreliable, that he says one thing and does another,'' Cozad said.
''It increases the effectiveness of the second ad no matter what
the subject may be.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-09-07-00 0216 </TRAILER>
