<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-07 02:18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Rochester prepares for world canal conference  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   ROCHESTER, N.Y. (AP) - Organizers of a world conference on
canals are preparing for about 300 devotees and experts that are
expected to attend next week's event.
</P>
<P>
   Visitors are expected from England, France, Spain, Canada and
the Czech Republic on Sept. 10 for the international discussion
about the future of the world's canal systems.
</P>
<P>
   They will be greeted Sunday with a flotilla of as many as 100
boats from across the state. The maritime parade will make its way
north up the Genesee River from the canal.
</P>
<P>
   ''People from around the world will see that we are putting a
lot more attention toward the Erie Canal,'' said Rochester Mayor
William A. Johnson Jr.
</P>
<P>
   The Erie Canal, which connected the Hudson and Lake Erie in
1825, was once an important commercial trade route that connected
the ports of New York and Albany to the western frontier.
</P>
<P>
   But the last remnants of commercial shipping left its banks in
1994 and it is now used exclusively for recreational purposes.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
