<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Gorbachev Chides Putin on Submarine  </HEADLINE>
By GERALD NADLER
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Looking relaxed, Mikhail Gorbachev joked that he
could only take one question at a time because he is 69. He then
launched into a warts-and-all assessment of Vladimir Putin,
criticizing the Russian president's ''mistakes of style.''
</P>
<P>
   Among Putin's missteps, Gorbachev said Wednesday, was waiting
four days to comment on the Kursk submarine tragedy and failing to
interrupt his vacation until a week after the sea disaster that
killed all 118 seamen aboard.
</P>
<P>
   Gorbachev, who himself was criticized for waiting several days
before commenting on the explosion at the Chernobyl nuclear power
station on April 26, 1986, said Putin's initial response to the
Kursk's sinking was ''inadequate.''
</P>
<P>
   ''He made a mistake,'' the former Soviet leader said.
</P>
<P>
   Gorbachev, who set the Soviet Union on the road to democracy,
also said Putin failed to explain to the people his economic
policies and legislative reforms to bolster governors as the
dominant leaders in Russia's regions.
</P>
<P>
   The former leader said he had pointed out these missteps to
Putin. An aide said Gorbachev met several times with Putin, with
one meeting lasting three hours.
</P>
<P>
   Gorbachev said earlier that the loss of the Kursk was part of an
''acute August crisis'' that also included a bombing at Moscow's
Pushkin Square that killed 12 people and a fire that roared through
Moscow's giant TV tower, leaving three people dead.
</P>
<P>
   ''The cause of the crisis was that the authorities showed a lack
of understanding of the need for informing the people -- of
glasnost,'' said Gorbachev, using the Russian word for ''openness''
that characterized his six years as the last Soviet communist
president.
</P>
<P>
   But Gorbachev, who was in New York to launch a Foundation for
the Development of Democracy and World Peace, said Putin's errors
were ''mostly mistakes of style'' and that the leader was sensitive
to criticism and ''recovered quickly.''
</P>
<P>
   ''We need to support the president ... despite the mistakes,''
Gorbachev said.
</P>
<P>
   He praised the Russian press for insisting authorities give the
facts about the crippled submarine, but bristled at what he said
was the Western press's ''lumping'' of his handling of the
Chernobyl explosion and Putin's slow response to the loss of the
Kursk. ''The coverage in the West smacked of the Cold War,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Gorbachev won the Nobel Peace Prize for his policies that
effectively ended the Cold War. He resigned on Dec. 25, 1991, when
the Soviet Union broke up, and was succeeded by Boris Yeltsin.
Yeltsin stepped down at the end of 1999 and was replaced by Putin.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-09-07-00 0251 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000907.0032 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-07 02:51 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Greek Victims Remember Quake  </HEADLINE>
By ELENA BECATOROS
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATHENS, Greece (AP) -- A dried wreath lies atop the rubble of a
factory complex that crumbled in seconds during a devastating
earthquake a year ago. A few yards away is a more bitter -- and some
say, more fitting -- memorial to the 38 people killed.
</P>
<P>
   The sun-parched flowers tell of the 143 people who died in the
5.9 magnitude quake on Sept. 7, 1999. The Ricomex factory had the
largest single death toll of the disaster.
</P>
<P>
   But a plain white marble monument, with a plaque reading
''Memorial of Disgrace'' above the names of the victims, stands as
another memorial to those who died at the household products plant.
</P>
<P>
   Relatives of those killed blame shoddy construction for the
collapse and are bitterly angry at Greek authorities for the slow
pace of an investigation into the factory's builders.
</P>
<P>
   ''The 'Disgrace' is for the state authorities who have been
silent until now, and for those who built this wreck,'' said
Stefanos Psiridis, whose sister Ioanna was killed in the collapse.
</P>
<P>
   In the quake's aftermath, Greek authorities pledged to
investigate the construction quality of buildings that went down.
But investigations have been slowed by missing documents and other
problems.
</P>
<P>
   The quake damaged 70,000 buildings around the capital, leaving
about 100,000 people homeless. The factory was located near the
quake epicenter in Athens' northern suburbs.
</P>
<P>
   Resettling and compensating quake victims and repairing damage
will cost $270 million, Planning Minister Costas Laliotis said.
</P>
<P>
   ''Although much has been done, there remains much more to do,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Earthquakes last summer in both Turkey and Greece -- and the aid
mutually offered by the two neighbors -- have been credited with
helping warm relations between the two regional rivals. More than
17,000 people were killed in the Aug. 17, 1999 quake in
northwestern Turkey.
</P>
<P>
   But the diplomatic advances mean little to those still living in
temporary housing in Athens.
</P>
<P>
   About 6,000 families are staying in converted containers in
state camps. Although the government is providing low-interest
loans to help quake victims rebuild their homes, many complain the
amounts are small and procedures to obtain them long-winded and
bureaucratic.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's hard and they ask for so many papers, so we gave up and
we're just funding the repairs ourselves,'' said Vasilis Kataras,
who said he had chosen to remain in his severely damaged home until
he began repairs a month ago.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's not possible to rebuild just with the money that they
give,'' said Mina Tordatzi as she watered plants in the garden she
has created outside her container home.
</P>
<P>
   Tordatzi, her husband and three grown children spent three
months living in a tent camp after the quake before they were moved
to the converted container camp in the Athens suburb of Menidi.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's OK living here -- better than living in those tents, in
that mess that we were in,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the homeless families seem resigned to the idea that
they'll be living in the camp for many more months. Well-tended
gardens have appeared, and raised wooden porches with red tiled
roofs have been added to the fronts of the plain containers.
</P>
<P>
   The family of Despina Iliadou built an extension to theirs to
create a living room.
</P>
<P>
   ''I took all my plants from my house and brought them here,''
said Iliadou, proudly displaying her tidy home. ''I can't stand
wretchedness.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-09-07-00 0251 </TRAILER>
