<HEADLINE> Federal aid sought in Nile virus fight  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   ROCHESTER, N.Y. (AP) - The state Association of Counties has
joined Gov. George Pataki in asking for federal help to pay for the
mounting costs of the West Nile virus.
</P>
<P>
   In a letter sent to the White House, the Association of Counties
said the high price comes from bird collection and testing,
mosquito control and trapping, pesticide spraying, public education
campaigns and virus surveillance.
</P>
<P>
   Keeping track of the virus is proving to be an expensive effort,
said Jody Gray, Ontario County acting health director. Most of the
cost comes from staff being tied up with virus issues instead of
their other duties, Gray said.
</P>
<P>
   The state does not have a firm figure of what it has spent or
even what it expects to spend this year - though it will exceed the
$14 million shelled out last year according to state Department of
Health spokeswoman Kristine Smith.
</P>
<P>
   New York will pay for as much as half of the expenses for
counties where a public health threat has been declared.
</P>
<P>
   Pataki in early August called on the federal government to
provide $20 million in federal assistance - $12 million more than
allocated for New York's West Nile virus efforts this year.
</P>
</TEXT>
