<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-07 08:29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Steroid Pills Said Better for Asthma  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON (AP) -- Doctors treating children for severe asthma
attacks should stick with standard steroid pills and not switch to
inhaled steroids, a study found.
</P>
<P>
   Steroid pills, such as prednisone, are safe when given for short
doses. But some pediatricians have wondered whether inhaled
steroids, which are easier to use, might work as well and be safer
still.
</P>
<P>
   The new study, conducted at the Hospital for Sick Children in
Toronto, attempted to settle this issue. One hundred children with
severe asthma attacks were randomly given either the inhaled or the
pill form of steroids.
</P>
<P>
   The results were clear: Children given prednisone pills
recovered more quickly.
</P>
<P>
   The report, published in Thursday's issue of the New England
Journal of Medicine, found that children given prednisone were
almost three times as likely to have an excellent response to
treatment and were only one-third as likely to be hospitalized.
</P>
<P>
   The study was partially financed by Glaxo Wellcome, which makes
Flonase, the inhaled steroid tested in the study.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-09-07-00 0829 </TRAILER>
