<HEADLINE> Dow Drops 43; Nasdaq Climbs 36  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks opened mixed Thursday after a handful of
companies warned of disappointing earnings.
</P>
<P>
   In the first hour of trading on Wall Street, the Dow Jones
industrial average was down 43.00 at 11,267.64.
</P>
<P>
   The Nasdaq composite index was up 36.92 at 4,050.26, and the
Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index was up 5.28 at 1,497.53.
</P>
<P>
   Before the market opened, DuPont, Campbell Soup, Circuit City
Stores and May Department Stores all warned their quarterly
earnings would be flat or below expectations.
</P>
<P>
   DuPont was down $4.25 at $42.75; Campbell was up 12.5 cents at
$25; Circuit City fell $1.25 to $26.50; and May was down 63 cents
at $23.06.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts have been warning investors to expect flat or lower
earnings because of the slowdown in economic growth. The Federal
Reserve has hiked interest rates six times since last summer, and
recent data suggest the economy is indeed slowing.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday and Wednesday, stocks including Intel and Micron fell
on analysts' continuing concerns about the health of the chip
business.
</P>
<P>
   The Russell 2000 index was up 1.53 at 537.66.
</P>
<P>
   Overseas, Japan's Nikkei stock average fell 0.32 percent. In
afternoon trading, Germany's DAX index was down .03 percent,
Britain's FT-SE 100 was down .25 percent, and France's CAC-40 was
down 0.30 percent.
</P>
</TEXT>
