<HEADLINE> Nasdaq Adds 75; Dow Loses 38  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Tech stocks moved higher Thursday after a
two-day downturn, while blue chips fell following another spate of
corporate earnings warnings.
</P>
<P>
   At midday on Wall Street, the Nasdaq composite index was up
75.33 at 4,088.67.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow Jones industrial average was down 37.83 at 11,272.81 and
the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index was up 8.71 at 1,500.96.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is a continuation of the rotation the market has become
accustomed to,'' said Bob Streed, senior vice president at Northern
Trust in Chicago. ''The money seems to flow back and forth.
Yesterday, investors took their money out of technology and put
into blue chips. Today, they're taking it out of blue chips and
putting it back into technology.''
</P>
<P>
   Tech stocks appeared to be having their best day so far in a
trading week abbreviated by the Labor Day holiday.
</P>
<P>
   Chipmaker Intel traded up $1.92 at $67.63 on the Nasdaq, after
tumbling for two days on an influential analyst's downgrade.
</P>
<P>
   Micron Technology, another chip maker that was downgraded on
Wednesday, was up $4 to $72.75 on the Big Board.
</P>
<P>
   DuPont, Campbell Soup, Circuit City Stores and May Department
Stores all warned Thursday that their quarterly earnings would be
flat or below expectations.
</P>
<P>
   DuPont was down $5 at $42; Campbell was up 19 cents at $25.06;
Circuit City fell $1.19 to $26.56; and May was down $1.31 cents at
$22.38.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts have been warning investors to expect flat or lower
earnings because of the slowdown in economic growth. The Federal
Reserve has hiked interest rates six times since last summer, and
recent data suggest the economy is indeed slowing.
</P>
<P>
   Shares of Restoration Hardware plummeted nearly 18 percent,
falling $1.06 at $4.92, after the home furnishings retailer said it
was in need of additional funding and had hired an investment bank
to help it find a new source of capital.
</P>
<P>
   Declining issues narrowly led advancers on the New York Stock
Exchange, where volume came to 450.77 million shares, compared to
454.21 million in the last session.
</P>
<P>
   The Russell 2000 index was up 2.38 at 538.70.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
