<HEADLINE> Former Bangladesh Premier Gets Bail  </HEADLINE>
By FARID HOSSAIN
<TEXT>
<P>
   DHAKA, Bangladesh (AP) -- A judge granted bail Thursday to former
Prime Minister Khaleda Zia, who has been charged with taking $35
million in kickbacks in the purchase of two planes for Bangladesh's
state-owned airlines.
</P>
<P>
   The charges involve two Airbus 310-300 passenger planes bought
by the Biman airlines from France's Airbus Industrie in 1995, when
Zia was prime minister.
</P>
<P>
   The anti-corruption bureau accused Zia's finance minister,
Saifur Rahman, and eight other former government officials of
helping her misappropriate $35 million in the purchase. They also
were granted bail Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Zia, who leads the main opposition Bangladesh Nationalist Party,
did not speak in court. But her lawyer Moudud Ahmed denied the
corruption charges and said they had been made up to undermine her
political image.
</P>
<P>
   Zia leads an alliance of four opposition parties campaigning for
the resignation of Prime Minister Sheikh Hasina's 4-year-old
government and for general elections ahead of the 2001 schedule.
</P>
<P>
   The alliance accuses Hasina's government of corruption,
incompetence and harassment of political opponents, a charge the
prime minister denies.
</P>
<P>
   Cheered by nearly 3,000 supporters, Zia drove in an open jeep to
the Metropolitan Sessions Court of Judge Ahmed Jamil Mostafa, who
accepted one surety in the amount of $2,000. The street procession
of her supporters created huge traffic jams in central Dhaka, the
capital.
</P>
<P>
   Zia sat on an armchair close to the wooden dock during the
half-hour court proceeding, after complaining of pain in her legs.
</P>
<P>
   Outside the courtroom, Zia's supporters scuffled with riot
police and chanted: ''Down with the corrupt government.'' No
injuries were reported.
</P>
<P>
   The corruption charges against Zia were filed in the court
Tuesday by the Bureau of Anti-Corruption after a two-year
investigation.
</P>
<P>
   The two planes in the latest kickback charges cost at total of
$150 million, at least $58 million more than the prevailing price
for the aircraft, according to the prosecution.
</P>
<P>
   ''We have found that Kuwait Airlines bought two similar Airbus
planes at $92 million the same year,'' said Harunur Rashid, an
investigator.
</P>
<P>
   Judge Mostafa sent the case to Dhaka District and Sessions Court
for future hearings. If convicted, Zia could be jailed for up to 10
years.
</P>
<P>
   Zia was granted bail in 1998 in two other cases of graft and
abuse of power filed by anti-corruption investigators after she
lost power in 1996.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-09-07-00 1249 </TRAILER>
