<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-07 12:50 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Congo Soldiers Fire on Each Other  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   KINSHASA, Congo (AP) -- Soldiers from different units engaged in
a deadly hours-long gunfight at the main military base in this
Central African capital city, officials said Thursday, forcing
civilians to flee the compound.
</P>
<P>
   No official death toll was made public, but military and
intelligence officials said nine soldiers were killed and 15
wounded in the fighting, which broke out before dawn Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ''A group of undisciplined elements opened fire on a police
patrol'' at Camp Tshatshi, Eddy Kapend, an aide to President
Laurent Kabila, said on national television. Some of Kabila's
bodyguards live at Camp Tshatshi, but it was unclear whether they
were involved in the fighting.
</P>
<P>
   Kapend said life at camp Tshatshi had returned to normal by late
Wednesday. Witnesses said civilians in the camp, mostly soldiers'
families, fled on foot with whatever belongings they could carry,
including electrical appliances.
</P>
<P>
   Solange Ngulu, a mother of four living in a shack community at
the edge of the camp, said she feared for her family's safety.
</P>
<P>
   ''The shooting went on and on for hours,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Camp Tshatshi was the scene of some of the earliest fighting
when Congo's civil war broke out in August 1998.
</P>
<P>
   The war in Congo, formerly known as Zaire, broke out when rebels
backed by one-time Kabila allies Rwanda and Uganda turned against
his regime, accusing it of corruption and of harboring Hutu
militiamen who fled Rwanda after committing genocide there in 1994.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
