<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Paksitan Bomb Kills 6 in Lahore  </HEADLINE>
By MUNIR AHMED
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAHORE, Pakistan (AP) -- A bomb ripped through a crowded market
in the eastern Pakistani border city of Lahore during the evening
rush hour Thursday, killing six people and injuring at least 33,
police said.
</P>
<P>
   The bomb exploded in Dharampura market in the eastern part of
the city, about two miles from Pakistan's border with India. No
group has claimed responsibility for the explosion, the fourth in
the city this year. Police said they made no immediate arrests.
</P>
<P>
   The crude homemade bomb, which weighed 4.4 pounds, damaged
several shops, shattered glass and caused a stampede. The bomb was
tied to a motorbike, which was destroyed in the explosion,
witnesses said. At least six people were critically injured,
doctors at a state-run hospital said. Two of those killed were
women.
</P>
<P>
   ''I heard a deafening explosion while shopping,'' said Ghulam
Mustafa, 42, who sustained head injuries. ''I don't remember what
happened next.''
</P>
<P>
   Another victim, Mohammed Nazeer, 18, who had burns on 30 percent
of his body, saw flames leaping as the explosion rocked the market.
</P>
<P>
   ''I fell from my bicycle. ... I don't where it is now,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Outside a city hospital's emergency ward, men and women wailed
and cried. Ali Imran, 22, said he carried his injured teen-age
brother to the hospital in a taxi.
</P>
<P>
   ''We both went out together. I stopped at a shop to buy milk,
while my brother went ahead,'' said a visibly shaken Imran.
''Moments later I heard a bang. ... I found my brother among the
victims. He has severe burn injuries. May God protect him.''
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday, a bomb explosion at a bus stop in Lahore killed three
people and injured 10 others. Police Inspector Mohammed Asghar said
similar explosive devices were used in both bombings.
</P>
<P>
   In recent months, there have been a series of bomb explosions in
major Pakistani cities in which scores of people have been killed
and many more injured. The Pakistani government routinely blames
neighboring India for acts of sabotage, while India accuses
Pakistan of fomenting terrorism.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
