<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-07 14:01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Arafat Rejects Jerusalem Compromise  </HEADLINE>
By KARIN LAUB
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS (AP) -- Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat has
rejected U.S. compromise proposals on Jerusalem, casting a pall
over what may be President Clinton's final push to secure a Mideast
peace deal.
</P>
<P>
   Sounding a similar tone, Israel Prime Minister Ehud Barak said
Thursday, ''Some of the ideas he has raised are beyond what we
believe we can accept.''
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, he said, ''If Chairman Arafat is ready to take
Clinton's ideas as the basis for negotiations, we will be ready to
contemplate it and to enter into such negotiations.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said Israel and the Palestinians remain committed to
reaching an agreement. However, with his latest mediation effort
unsuccessful -- he met back-to-back Wednesday night with the Israeli
and Palestinian leaders -- it was not clear what his next move could
be.
</P>
<P>
   Barak is staying in New York through the weekend, but Arafat is
expected to head home Friday to chair a Palestine Liberation
Organization conference that is to set a date for proclaiming
Palestinian independence.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think they basically went well,'' Clinton said of his talks
Wednesday with Barak and Arafat. ''They understand the time is
short.''
</P>
<P>
   Barak noted that Congress was scheduled to adjourn in October.
''Since there is a clear need to mobilize major sums of money in
order to support such an agreement being glued together, I believe
that time is running out in terms of being able to solve it,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   State Department spokesman Richard Boucher said Dennis Ross, the
senior U.S. mediator on the Mideast, was holding separate meetings
Thursday with Israeli and Palestinian officials.
</P>
<P>
   At the heart of the conflict are rival Israeli and Palestinian
claims to a 36-acre walled compound in Jerusalem's Old City, part
of the traditionally Arab eastern sector of the city.
</P>
<P>
   The site is known to Jews as the Temple Mount, home to the
holiest of Jewish temples. Muslims revere it as Haram as-Sharif, or
Noble Sanctuary, home to two mosques that mark the spot where
prophet Mohammed ascended to heaven.
</P>
<P>
   In Wednesday evening's 90-minute meeting with Clinton, on the
sidelines of the U.N. Millennium Summit, Arafat told the president
he would not drop demands for Palestinian sovereignty over all of
east Jerusalem, which was captured by Israel in the 1967 Mideast
war.
</P>
<P>
   ''We were clear that we are not ready to make concessions on the
issue of Palestinian sovereignty in Jerusalem and on the issue of
the Haram as-Sharif,'' said Palestinian negotiator Nabil Shaath.
</P>
<P>
   Arafat told the president that his hands are tied and that any
compromise on Jerusalem would be met by shock and outrage in the
Arab and Islamic world.
</P>
<P>
   In talks with Secretary of State Madeleine Albright, the
Palestinian leader played down Jewish religious claims to the holy
site. Palestinian officials described the session as difficult, and
said voices were raised at times.
</P>
<P>
   Shaath said there was a possibility that Clinton would hold
another round of separate talks with Barak and Arafat, but that no
time has been set. He said lower-level negotiations, in the
presence of a U.S. mediator, might resume in the region next week.
</P>
<P>
   Israel has said it was willing to consider creative ideas on how
to share Jerusalem, but only after Arafat has signaled some
willingness to compromise.
</P>
<P>
   ''With a little bit of good will, of creativity and flexibility
on the Palestinian side, I believe the Jerusalem issue may be
settled,'' Israel's deputy defense minister, Ephraim Sneh, told The
Associated Press in Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
   A U.S. compromise proposal, according to Palestinian officials,
would have given Israel sovereignty over the Western Wall, one of
the remnants of the temple, while the Palestinians would have
control over the mosques. The remaining areas in the walled
compound would have been placed under divine sovereignty.
</P>
<P>
   Palestinian negotiator Yasser Abed Rabbo said Thursday that
divine sovereignty and other compromise proposals, such as
deferring a deal on Jerusalem, were no longer on the table.
</P>
<P>
   The inconclusive high-level meetings came just a week before the
Sept. 13 deadline for a final Israeli-Palestinian peace treaty.
</P>
<P>
   Arafat has reserved the right to proclaim statehood, even
without Israel's blessing, on that day, but has said a final
decision is up to the PLO's top policy-making body, which is to
convene Saturday. Arafat has hinted that the PLO council was likely
to delay a statehood proclamation until later this year.
</P>
<P>
   White House spokesman Joe Lockhart dismissed Sept. 13 as ''an
artificial date.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-09-07-00 1401 </TRAILER>
