<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-07 14:23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Turkey Police Bar Gays From Resort  </HEADLINE>
By HARMONIE TOROS
<TEXT>
<P>
   ISTANBUL, Turkey (AP) -- Passengers on a gay-oriented cruise
expressed anger and disappointment and Turkish officials scrambled
to apologize Thursday, a day after police barred the tourists from
visiting the ancient ruins of Ephesus.
</P>
<P>
   ''I haven't seen anything like this anywhere,'' said Bruno
Gideon of Toronto, a cruise passenger. ''I didn't think a country
like Turkey would act like this. I still don't understand.''
</P>
<P>
   The cruise liner Olympic Voyager was taking 800 passengers, many
from the United States, on a seven-day tour with stops in Egypt,
Israel and Greece. On Wednesday, the cruise stopped at the Turkish
Aegean port of Kusadasi and passengers boarded buses for Ephesus,
which draws thousands of tourists each year.
</P>
<P>
   After allowing several groups to leave, police turned back at
least two other buses. The sudden change apparently came after they
realized the passengers were all homosexuals, the tourists and
members of the tour's crew said.
</P>
<P>
   Police also chased after buses headed from the cruise liner to
the Ephesus. They caught one in the town of Selcuk, some two miles
from the Ephesus ruins, and sent it back to the cruise liner, said
Erkunt Oner of Seamer Tour Agency, which organized the land tours.
</P>
<P>
   ''When we got back, a guy from the ship just said 'Get on the
ship as fast as you can,''' said Ken Damon from Tucson, Ariz.
</P>
<P>
   Damon said he had planned to return to Kusadasi for a two-week
vacation after the cruise. ''But we don't want to be in a country
that doesn't respect us,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Although gay artists, singers and belly dancers are popular in
Muslim Turkey, homosexuality is still taboo and gays complain that
they are often discriminated against, especially by police.
</P>
<P>
   ''All they said was 'No pass,''' said Edward Timblyn of Houston.
''I was disappointed, being stuck on the ship all day.''
</P>
<P>
   The mayor of Kusadasi and other Turkish authorities tried to
make amends Thursday, arguing that local police acted on their own.
</P>
<P>
   ''We were not able to receive a clear explanation from police
for their action. They only said they were obeying instructions
from the Interior Ministry,'' said Can Tekmen, spokesman for the
mayor of Kusadasi.
</P>
<P>
   But Mithat Dumanli, a ministry spokesman, said he was unaware of
any orders from the ministry.
</P>
<P>
   ''In the end, the mayor went to the ship to apologize,'' Tekmen
said. ''This is not good publicity for Kusadasi or for Turkey. At
the moment, we need all the tourists we can get.''
</P>
<P>
   Tourism Minister Erkan Mumcu also tried to diffuse tensions.
</P>
<P>
   ''We are not in a position to make judgments about peoples'
sexual preferences,'' Mumcu was quoted as saying by the Anatolia
news agency. ''They are in Istanbul now, and I think they will end
their visit without meeting any more problems.''
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Embassy spokesman Jess Baily said the embassy had brought
the case to the attention of Turkish authorities and ''was pleased
with their response thereafter.''
</P>
<P>
   Cody Hamilton of Durham, N.C., who was among those whose bus
made it through to Ephesus, was relieved that authorities had
apologized to his group.
</P>
<P>
   ''The fact that this kind of ignorance is not tolerated by
higher authorities is very important,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the passengers, including some tourists from the
Netherlands and Britain, toured Istanbul before their scheduled
departure for Athens.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-09-07-00 1423 </TRAILER>
