<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-07 14:30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thrill Ride Near Church Spurs Debate  </HEADLINE>
By CHRISTOPHER BODEEN
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIJING (AP) -- A bungee jump in downtown Beijing is the latest
thrill for China's growing, entertainment-seeking middle class. Not
so thrilled, however, are parishioners at a 350-year-old Catholic
church across the street.
</P>
<P>
   The new ride has some complaining that the Chinese capital's
anything-goes approach to development has gone to far.
</P>
<P>
   Located on Wangfujing, Beijing's premier shopping street, the
100-foot-high ride is the latest attempt by the area's merchants
and officials to drum up business.
</P>
<P>
   However, once the ride opens for business next month, services
at the East Church, 150 feet away, could be punctuated by the
screams of bungee jumpers.
</P>
<P>
   Already, the jump's two crane-like towers -- which drop three
people seated in a cage -- are visible through the church windows.
</P>
<P>
   That has many parishioners unhappy about living under the bungee
ride's shadow. And for Mi Songyi, a member of the city's municipal
council, the attraction is a blight on the district.
</P>
<P>
   The juxtaposition of the sacred and whimsical reflects the
communist government's longtime outlook on religion -- scant regard
that at times turns to outright persecution.
</P>
<P>
   It also reflects how preservation has often had to take a back
seat as Beijing's leaders transform the capital from a city of
stubby courtyard houses to a metropolis of broad avenues and modern
high rises.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't see any clash between the bungee jumping and church,''
insisted Zhao Haixiang, a college student majoring in art who was
sketching the church Thursday. ''Religion ought to be part of life.
We shouldn't make it too serious.''
</P>
<P>
   Diversity is Beijing's strength, Zhao said, adding that the city
should jumble the sacred with the profane.
</P>
<P>
   City planners are turning Wangfujing into a pedestrian mall to
give Beijing's growing middle class a place to play.
</P>
<P>
   Like much of Beijing, the street itself is a wild mix of
contrasts, where run-down gray brick courtyard houses abut glitzy
department stores. A McDonalds stands next to staid government book
shops. The modern, colorful look of the bungee jump contrasts the
dour, gray brick East Church.
</P>
<P>
   The church has benefited from an ongoing restoration that has
spruced up the interior and turned the square in front of it into a
public park.
</P>
<P>
   Dating to 1655, East Church was erected on the guidance of
Catholic missionaries during China's imperial past. It was reopened
for use in the early 1980s as part of the government's official
Catholic church. Beijing does not recognize the authority of the
Vatican, and believers who remain loyal to the pope in an
underground church face harassment and arrest.
</P>
<P>
   Recent years have seen scattered efforts to restore some old
Buddhist temples and churches, neglected for decades after the
officially atheistic communists took power in 1949.
</P>
<P>
   But development often hedges in on preservation efforts.
Beijing's famous Lama temple is neighbor to a freeway and the
Buddhist shrine's base is an entrance to the subway.
</P>
<P>
   Mi, the municipal councilwoman, said the clash between the
bungee jump and East Church went too far. She told the
English-language China Daily that bungee jumping will damage the
feel of the street.
</P>
<P>
   But neighborhood Catholics appear resigned to accommodation.
Cheap thrills and mass consumption have become China's new culture
and imported religions have to adapt, said Wang Rouwang, a Catholic
whose family has lived in Beijing for over 200 years.
</P>
<P>
   The church's elderly watchman, meanwhile, said services might be
disrupted by the jump, but he warned protesting would be futile.
</P>
<P>
   ''That's the prerogative of the government and there's nothing
you or I can do about it,'' said the man, who gave his surname, Wu.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-09-07-00 1430 </TRAILER>
