<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-07 15:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Teacher strikes are rare in New York  </HEADLINE>
By ANNY KUO
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) - Public school teachers in New York have not
been prone to strikes for nearly two decades, making the job action
by teachers in Buffalo a somewhat rare occurrence, observers said
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Since the 1982-83 school year, New York has seen 10 strikes by
teachers in kindergarten through 12th grade, with just four
happening after 1990.
</P>
<P>
   ''By and large, the level of cooperation between bargaining
units and school districts has been very high. Buffalo's problem
was chronic,'' said Robin Rapaport, vice president of the
42,000-member National Education Association-New York, the parent
union of the Buffalo Federation of Teachers.
</P>
<P>
   In the state's second-largest school district, 3,700 teachers
went on strike Thursday morning after union executives rejected a
contract offer by the Board of Education. The walkout came on the
second day of classes, and the district canceled school for its
47,000 students.
</P>
<P>
   ''Buffalo is an aberration,'' said David Ernst, spokesman for
the state School Boards Association. ''Unions all over the state
are either settling contracts or remaining at the bargaining table.
For some reason the Buffalo union is thinking different.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1967, New York enacted the Public Employees Fair Employment
Act, commonly known as the Taylor Law. The law gave public
employees the right to organize and established procedures to
settle collective bargaining disputes.
</P>
<P>
   But the Taylor Law also made it illegal for public employees,
including teachers, to strike. Penalties for striking include a
loss of two days' pay for each day of the strike and possibly
additional disciplinary action.
</P>
<P>
   In Buffalo's case, teachers could face potential jail time for
defying a court injunction prohibiting the action.
</P>
<P>
   During the last teachers' strike in the state - a three-day
walkout in Yonkers in October 1999 - teachers were liable for six
days' pay for violating the Taylor Law. The 2,100-member teachers
union was also fined $50,000 for violating a court injunction that
took effect when the strike began.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Frey, president of the Yonkers Federation of Teachers,
said his union has no regrets about last year's strike. But he
acknowledged that fewer and fewer unions are resorting to job
actions because they ''realize that it hurts the whole educational
system and it's best to be avoided.''
</P>
<P>
   In all, there were 112 strikes since the inception of the Taylor
Law. Records show that the largest number of teacher strikes - 20
districts - happened in the 1975-76 school year. Buffalo was one of
the affected districts that year; its teachers struck for 13 days.
</P>
<P>
   The number of strikes dipped dramatically following the passage
of the Triborough Amendment to the Taylor Law in 1982, said Linda
Rosenblatt, spokeswoman for the New York State United Teachers
union. The amendment mandated that when a contract expires, the
terms and conditions of the old contract continue until a new
agreement takes effect.
</P>
<P>
   ''That has really done a lot to provide labor peace,''
Rosenblatt said.
</P>
<P>
   But Ernst said the Triborough Amendment gave teachers ''no
incentives to settle contracts'' since most are able to receive
benefits and pay raises spelled out in expired agreements. Instead,
contract negotiations are dragged out until teachers and unions
feel the economic pressure to seek a new contract, he said.
</P>
<P>
   According to NYSUT, 122 teacher locals began the 2000-01 school
year without contracts - the lowest number in at least nine years.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-09-07-00 1514 </TRAILER>
