<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-07 15:16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indian Affairs Marks Anniversary  </HEADLINE>
By MATT KELLEY
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Bureau of Indian Affairs will mark its
175th anniversary Friday with speeches, songs and ceremonies at
Interior Department headquarters. But there's a hitch: The 175th
anniversary was last year.
</P>
<P>
   Kevin Gover, the Pawnee Indian who heads the BIA, chuckled when
asked about the delay. He said so much attention was directed at
the Interior Department's 150th anniversary in 1999 there was no
time to arrange ceremonies for the BIA.
</P>
<P>
   ''The department's 150th got a lot of attention and our 175th
got none,'' Gover said. ''So we said, 'We're going to do it
ourselves, even if we are late.'''
</P>
<P>
   Besides, Gover said, the commemoration will be more solemn than
celebratory.
</P>
<P>
   ''To call it a celebration doesn't seem appropriate somehow,
given the devastating, often tragic history,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The BIA was created March 11, 1824, as part of the War
Department -- when the government was trying to solve the ''Indian
problem'' through military means.
</P>
<P>
   The BIA moved to the Interior Department years later, but it
still was run by non-Indians whose goal was to eradicate Indian
governments, lands and cultures. Only in the past three decades has
the BIA's mission changed to help promote tribal autonomy.
</P>
<P>
   Now about 90 percent of the BIA's 10,000 employees are Indian,
but decades of poor funding and lax oversight have left the agency
plagued by mismanagement and inefficiency, Gover says. He has said
one of his goals was to bring the agency to basic competence before
he leaves office with the Clinton administration.
</P>
<P>
   Gover plans a speech at Friday's commemoration to discuss the
bureau's history and its future as a force to help tribes.
Officials also plan to line the hallway leading to Gover's office
with flags from some of the 558 federally recognized Indian tribes.
</P>
<P>
   ''The real acknowledgment is how the bureau has changed from
getting rid of Indians to having Indian people who are directing
policy here,'' said BIA spokeswoman Nedra Darling, a member of the
Prairie Band of Potawatomi Indians. ''It's time to put the course
for the BIA ahead of us.''
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   Bureau of Indian Affairs:
http://www.doi.gov/bureau-indian-affairs.html
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-09-07-00 1516 </TRAILER>
