<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-07 15:22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> It turns out much-maligned N.Y. utilities are a hot commodity  </HEADLINE>
By JOEL STASHENKO
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) - A little more than four years ago, a Niagara
Mohawk Power Corp. stockholder got up at a raucous meeting of the
utility's shareholders in Albany and stared down CEO William Davis
and other top company executives.
</P>
<P>
   ''The management has done a lot of damage to the future of this
company,'' the shareholder said to the applause of several hundred
fellow investors.
</P>
<P>
   Not so. Not judging by this week's announcement that an American
subsidiary of a London company is proposing to buy the
Syracuse-based utility for more than $3 billion in cash and stock.
National Grid Group of Westborough, Mass., which stands to become
the ninth-largest electric utility in the United States if the
acquisition goes through, would also assume nearly $6 billion in
Niagara Mohawk debt.
</P>
<P>
   For long-suffering Niagara Mohawk shareholders, who saw their
dividends dwindle and then vanish in the mid-1990s, the proposed
purchase is a godsend. National Grid is offering a 37 percent
premium on the value of outstanding Niagara Mohawk shares.
</P>
<P>
   And for people who watch New York's utilities or pay utility
bills, the huge National Grid-Niagara Mohawk transaction is an even
bigger surprise.
</P>
<P>
   It turns out that the debt-saddled utility, which just a few
years ago was threatening to declare bankruptcy before it got out
from under state-mandated contracts with independent power
producers, was a hot commodity.
</P>
<P>
   And it's not just Niagara Mohawk. As utility deregulation
progresses in New York, it is becoming clear that the state's
much-maligned utilities - lambasted for decades by politicians and
ratepayers for high rates, unreliable power plants and indifferent
service - are regarded as valuable properties within the U.S.
energy industry.
</P>
<P>
   When the New York Power Authority sought to sell its state-owned
FitzPatrick and Indian Point 3 nuclear power plants this year it
attracted a record offer of $638 million. Then another company
stepped forward with an unsolicited bid $50 million higher.
</P>
<P>
   Promoted by Democrats in the state Assembly, the unintended
bidding war finally ended with a $967 million offer from a New
Orleans-based energy conglomerate. It is the highest amount ever
for nuclear generating facilities in the United States and the
biggest sale of state property in New York history.
</P>
<P>
   Other New York utilities have similarly found eager, and
well-heeled, buyers for the generating stations they are shedding
at the encouragement of the Pataki administration as part of the
deregulation of the state's utility industry. In broad outline,
deregulation calls for traditional utilities to become the
deliverers of electricity they buy on an open - and presumably more
competitive - market.
</P>
<P>
   Consumers are supposed to see lower prices and more choice in
their providers of utility services.
</P>
<P>
   State Assemblyman Paul Tonko, an Amsterdam Democrat who heads
the Assembly's energy committee, said he is not surprised at the
prices some components of New York's utility industry have
commanded. But he said he is dismayed at who will - or will not -
reap the benefits of the sales.
</P>
<P>
   ''I've heard a lot of talk in the last 24 hours about
'maximizing (Niagara Mohawk) shareholder value,''' Tonko said.
''Everyone has analyzed this windfall as a dose of maximizing and I
think I have heard several times the use of the word 'premiums.'
Well, where is the premium for ratepayers? Where is the maximizing
of benefits for consumers?''
</P>
<P>
   With the billions upon billions of dollars they have paid over
the years in rates, customers of Niagara Mohawk should get ''their
slice of the bacon'' from the sale of the utility and its assets,
he insisted.
</P>
<P>
   ''The ratepayers made them the strong company they are,'' Tonko
said. ''When they go to the market and speak gleefully of the
premiums that are offered, that came via the ratepayers' pocket and
they (ratepayers) ought not be disregarded in the bottom line.''
</P>
<P>
   Assembly Democrats announced Thursday they will hold public
hearings on Sept. 27 in Buffalo and Oct. 11 in Albany on the
proposed acquisition, which has to be approved by Niagara Mohawk
and National Grid stockholders as well as state and federal
regulators.
</P>
<P>
   Tonko faulted the Pataki administration for failing to establish
standards for consumer benefit when utilities in the state are
sold, or the utilities sell off power generating stations built
with the help of ratepayer money.
</P>
<P>
   While being very precise about the benefits of the sale to
Niagara Mohawk stockholders, top executives of Niagara Mohawk and
National Grid were far less so this week when explaining the
possible benefits to the 1.5 million Niagara Mohawk customers.
</P>
<P>
   National Grid's Richard Sergel said the deal would ''stabilize
electricity deliver costs'' in the upstate New York market which
Niagara Mohawk dominates. Davis said, ''We would anticipate a
variety of savings that would result from this.''
</P>
<P>
   The chairwoman of the state Public Service Commission, Maureen
Helmer, said her agency will review the proposed sale to see if it
is in the ''public interest.''
</P>
<P>
   Joel Stashenko is Capitol Editor for The Associated Press in
Albany. He can be reached at P.O. Box 7165, Capitol Station,
Albany, N.Y., 12224.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
