<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-07 15:27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nasdaq Gains 82; Dow Sheds 29  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- High-tech stocks moved higher Thursday after a
two-day downturn, while blue chips fell following another spate of
corporate earnings warnings.
</P>
<P>
   In midfternoon trading on Wall Street, the Nasdaq composite
index was up 82.00 at 4,095.54, buoyed by the same stocks that
investors couldn't wait to get rid of earlier this week.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow Jones industrial average was down 29.32 at 11,281.32 and
the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index was up 12.17 at 1,504.42.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is a continuation of the rotation the market has become
accustomed to,'' said Bob Streed, senior vice president at Northern
Trust in Chicago. ''The money seems to flow back and forth.
Yesterday, investors took their money out of technology and put
into blue chips. Today, they're taking it out of blue chips and
putting it back into technology.''
</P>
<P>
   Tech stocks appeared to be having their best day so far in a
trading week abbreviated by the Labor Day holiday.
</P>
<P>
   Chipmaker Intel traded up $2.05 at $67.75 on the Nasdaq, after
tumbling for two days on an influential analyst's downgrade.
</P>
<P>
   Micron Technology, another chip maker that was downgraded by
another analyst on Wednesday, was up $5.63 to $74.38 on the Big
Board.
</P>
<P>
   But investors moved away from blue chips, however. Shares of
DuPont fell $5.56 to $41.44 after the chemical company warned that
earnings would be below expectations because of decreased demand
and higher costs.
</P>
<P>
   ''DuPont essentially said today it is going to have the same
kind of earnings as it did four years ago,'' said Mike Weiner, a
managing director at Banc One Investment Advisors in Columbus,
Ohio. ''Because DuPont is down, a lot of other companies are too.''
</P>
<P>
   Campbell Soup, Circuit City Stores and May Department Stores
also warned Thursday that their quarterly earnings would be flat or
below expectations. By midafternoon, Circuit City fell 88 cents to
$26.88 per share and May was down $1.38 at $22.31. Shares of
Campbell were up 25 cents at $25.13;
</P>
<P>
   Shares of Restoration Hardware dropped nearly 19 percent,
falling $1.13 at $4.88, after the home furnishings retailer said it
was in need of additional funding and had hired an investment bank
to help it find a new source of capital.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts have been warning investors to expect flat or lower
earnings because of the slowdown in economic growth. The Federal
Reserve has hiked interest rates six times since last summer, and
recent data suggest the economy is indeed slowing.
</P>
<P>
   Also Thursday, MP3 continued to decline, falling $1.69 -- more
than 21 percent -- to $6.19. A federal judge ruled Wednesday that
MP3.com, which allows people to listen to songs over the Internet
but not download them to their computers, violated Universal's
copyrights.
</P>
<P>
   Declining issues narrowly led advancers on the New York Stock
Exchange, where volume came to 776.58 million shares, compared to
787.78 million in the last session.
</P>
<P>
   The Russell 2000 index was up 3.09 at 539.41.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
