<HEADLINE> Israel Officers Dismissed After Raid  </HEADLINE>
By MARK LAVIE
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEL AVIV, Israel (AP) -- Faulty judgment and operational mistakes
led to Israeli army snipers killing three of their own soldiers
during a botched attempt to capture a Palestinian militant,
Israel's top military commander said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Accepting the recommendations of a high-level military committee
that investigated the raid, army chief of staff Lt. Gen. Shaul
Mofaz dismissed West Bank commander Brig. Gen. Shlomo Oren; the
Duvdevan anti-terror unit commander, known only as Lt. Col. Miki; a
squad commander and the snipers.
</P>
<P>
   Soldiers from the Duvdevan unit entered the West Bank village of
Assira Ashmalia the night of Aug. 27 and surrounded a house where
Hamas militant bombmaker Mahmoud Abu Hanoud was hiding. While three
Israeli soldiers were killed and another wounded by their comrades'
gunfire, Hanoud escaped into Palestinian-controlled territory.
</P>
<P>
   A report on the operation found that it was too complicated,
involved too many separate units and was badly implemented.
Soldiers were given an option of climbing to a rooftop across from
the house where Hanoud was hiding, leading snipers to conclude that
they were terrorists and open fire on them, Mofaz said.
</P>
<P>
   Visibly exasperated, he said it was unclear how Hanoud managed
to escape. If his forces had initiated contact as they were
supposed to, Hanoud would have been captured, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Hanoud, who was wounded, later turned himself in to Palestinian
authorities. He was sentenced to 12 years in a Palestinian prison.
</P>
<P>
   Israel says Hanoud was responsible for deadly bomb attacks in
downtown Jerusalem in 1997 and several more attacks since then. He
was at the top of Israel's most-wanted list in the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
   The night of the raid, villagers spotted the first Israeli unit
and warned Hanoud by telephone, Mofaz said. Hanoud opened fire
first, which caused the operation to be speeded up and led to the
errors.
</P>
<P>
   In the future, Mofaz said, such missions would be less
intricate.
</P>
<P>
   Duvdevan, which means ''cherry,'' was set up during the 1987-93
Palestinian uprising. Soldiers in the unit often masqueraded as
Palestinians to infiltrate villages, capturing or killing
resistance leaders.
</P>
<P>
   Despite his harsh criticism of the operation, Mofaz insisted
that the special unit still has a role.
</P>
<P>
   ''There is no substitute for a unit like Duvdevan in fighting
terrorism,'' he told a news conference.
</P>
<P>
   The Palestinian Authority controls about 40 percent of the West
Bank, including cities and most towns and villages. In some areas,
including Assira Ashmalia, Palestinians handle civilian matters,
but Israel maintains security control.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-09-07-00 1531 </TRAILER>
