<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Andrew F. Capoccia, personal bankruptcy lawyer, is disbarred  </HEADLINE>
By JOEL STASHENKO
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) - Andrew F. Capoccia, a personal bankruptcy
lawyer whose aggressive tactics frustrated creditors, judges and
other attorneys, was disbarred Thursday by a state appeals court.
</P>
<P>
   The Appellate Division of state Supreme Court ruled that
Capoccia continued to employ the courtroom strategy of filing claim
upon claim against opponents even though he had been warned they
were often ''without merit'' and sometimes bordered on frivolous.
</P>
<P>
   The Albany lawyer's litigating strategies ''have deleteriously
burdened this state's judicial system well beyond any reasonable or
defensible effort to represent clients,'' the five-member appeals
court said in an unsigned, unanimous decision.
</P>
<P>
   The judges noted that Capoccia kept up his tactics despite being
warned by ''scores of justices and judges throughout this state to
discontinue these practices.'' He also had been previously
suspended from practicing law for six months in 1983 for filing an
inaccurate record and other misconduct and had 221 sanctions
against him assessed by courts totaling $1.43 million, the
appellate division noted.
</P>
<P>
   ''In order to protect the public, preserve the integrity and
reputation of the Bar and deter similar misconduct, we conclude
that respondent (Capoccia) should be disbarred,'' the judges said.
</P>
<P>
   Capoccia's name became well known to the public because of the
heavy advertising he did on television for his high-volume debt
resolution services.
</P>
<P>
   But opponents said his practice was built upon countersuing the
creditors of clients, asserting consumer protection claims and
technical violations of credit statutes. In many cases, they
argued, the claims had been cribbed from the cases of other
Capoccia clients and bore little or no relevance to the case at
hand.
</P>
<P>
   The real aim of his tactics was to get creditors to settle for
pennies on the dollar rather than face protracted litigation to get
their money from Capoccia's clients, legal conduct officials
charged.
</P>
<P>
   Capoccia's lawyer Hal Lieberman said his only reaction to
Thursday's ruling was ''disappointment.'' He said he would seek to
appeal the determination to the state's highest court, the Court of
Appeals.
</P>
<P>
   Among the other high-profile lawyers representing Capoccia
before the appellate division were Milton Mollen, former presiding
justice in the state's Second Judicial Department, and Gerald
Lefcourt, former president of the National Association of Criminal
Defense Lawyers.
</P>
<P>
   In June, the appellate division found Capoccia guilty of
misconduct. On Thursday, it again rejected his continuing argument
that he had been denied a hearing as part of those proceedings. It
also brushed aside his assertions that his tactics had, in fact,
been upheld by judges.
</P>
<P>
   According to the Committee on Professional Standards, Capoccia
had paid only about $16,000 of the $1.43 million in sanctions
levied against him.
</P>
<P>
   State Attorney General Eliot Spitzer is suing Capoccia in a
separate case, contending that his practice represented ''vast
consumer fraud'' because he allegedly failed to deliver the relief
for his clients from creditors and debt which Capoccia promised.
</P>
<P>
   ''This merely proves that Andrew Capoccia has not been playing
by the rules, whether in the courtroom or with his clients,''
Spitzer said Thursday. ''I am not surprised at this result. We
obviously will continue our efforts in our ongoing litigation with
him.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-09-07-00 1552 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000907.0088 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-07 16:03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Greg Kinnear Has Role-Reversal  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Greg Kinnear is enjoying some real-life role
reversal.
</P>
<P>
   The co-star of the new movie ''Nurse Betty'' remembers once
worked as a rookie broadcaster at the Cannes Film Festival in 1990.
</P>
<P>
   ''I basically had to run up to people like Anthony Quinn and
squeeze out a few questions before being dragged off by
publicists,'' he said in US Weekly.
</P>
<P>
   At this year's festival, Kinnear himself was buttonholed by
reporters and was extremely accommodating.
</P>
<P>
   ''If I saw somebody with a tape recorder, I was running up to
them, saying, 'You need a soundbite? You need a quote?' I was
entirely accessible, just to set the karmic record straight,'' he
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
