<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-07 16:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Democratic candidate bold on paper, understated in person  </HEADLINE>
By LAURENCE ARNOLD
<TEXT>
<P>
   POINT PLEASANT BEACH, N.J. (AP) - The atmosphere in Martell's
Tiki Bar is thoroughly laid back. So is the visiting candidate.
</P>
<P>
   The final weekend of summer finds Democrat Jon Corzine on a bar
stool, casually telling two guys in tank tops that he'd like to
''spend a little money on our schools, a little money on our health
care.''
</P>
<P>
   That's an understatement. In fact, Corzine proposes universal
health care for all Americans and universal preschool for all
children.
</P>
<P>
   His official proposals may be big-government bold, but Corzine
is casual and unassuming in person. Approaching people on the
boardwalk, he asks gently, ''Mind if I say hello?''
</P>
<P>
   Corzine, the former chairman of Goldman Sachs &AMP; Co., has defined
himself with his record expenditure of $36 million during the
primary - most of it from a personal wealth estimated at $400
million.
</P>
<P>
   He was stingy in his public appearances during the Democratic
primary, in which he defeated former Gov. Jim Florio. But he has
increased his public profile of late. He greets voters at train
stations, addresses friendly groups like labor organizations and
rarely mentions his Republican opponent, U.S. Rep. Bob Franks.
</P>
<P>
   Corzine, 53, insists that a massive advertising campaign is no
substitute for shaking hands.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's absolutely, vitally important to do this,'' he says,
halfway through a Labor Day weekend full of campaign events, ''so
the word ripples out that the guy you see on TV is the guy that's
real.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked for words that best describe the real Jon Corzine,
campaign manager Tom Shea suggests ''sincere, authentic,
comfortable, genuine.''
</P>
<P>
   Up early on Sunday morning, Corzine attends services at Second
Baptist Church in Long Branch, where the Rev. Aaron Gibson Sr.
invites him to introduce himself.
</P>
<P>
   ''Jon Corzine of Christ Church in Summit,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Corzine has declined Gibson's invitation to address the
congregation, saying, ''I came to worship.''
</P>
<P>
   He does meet after the service with about 20 congregants and
church leaders in a classroom. Only in this intimate setting does
Corzine hint at the scale of his proposals, which critics call
liberal and he calls progressive.
</P>
<P>
   He says universal health care - which proved too ambitious for
President Clinton - is at ''the top of my agenda'' and chides Vice
President Al Gore for advocating too incremental an approach to
helping the uninsured.
</P>
<P>
   Corzine has wounded himself with a propensity to put his foot in
his mouth. The most recent occasion was this week, when he told
reporters, emphatically but incorrectly, that he had voted in a
1998 referendum.
</P>
<P>
   Corzine's public image suffered its biggest blow during the
primary when he was accused of uttering a joke about
Italian-Americans and ''cement shoes.'' He said he did not remember
making the remark but apologized nonetheless.
</P>
<P>
   If inexperience carries pitfalls, however, it also has its
virtues. Unlike many politicians who seem constantly to scan a
crowd for familiar faces, Corzine remains focused on the
conversation at hand.
</P>
<P>
   Charles Flum of Beachwood approaches Corzine on the Atlantic
City boardwalk and recalls their first meeting, when Flum asked a
specific question about a Coast Guard facility.
</P>
<P>
   ''You said you didn't know anything about it,'' Flum tells
Corzine now. ''That honesty is what will give me your vote.''
</P>
<P>
   Corzine wears his authenticity on his face - quite literally. As
he considered running for Senate, some advisers told him he would
need to lose the beard he'd worn for 21 years.
</P>
<P>
   But the beard, much grayer than Corzine's brown hair, is still
there. Shaving it off, Corzine said, would have been a statement
that ''I do whatever it takes to get elected.''
</P>
<P>
   While most of his encounters over the weekend are pleasant,
there is an undercurrent of cynicism.
</P>
<P>
   ''Why is he a Democrat? He's a billionaire!'' exclaims Marilyn
Redder of Point Pleasant Beach after telling Corzine that he, of
all people, should favor running schools more like a business.
</P>
<P>
   Another Republican, Bill Fitzell of Andover, gives Corzine a
chilly reception on the Atlantic City boardwalk and later says,
''He hasn't made anything other than money. You know what that
means? He hasn't produced any tangible goods.''
</P>
<P>
   The biggest adjustment to politics, Corzine says, is the loss of
privacy. His wife, Joanne, joins him infrequently on the campaign
trail.
</P>
<P>
   A guest at Martell's Tiki Bar asks Corzine his thoughts on the
prolonged kiss that Gore planted on his wife, Tipper, during the
Democratic National Convention.
</P>
<P>
   Corzine smiles and replies, ''My wife warned me that if I even
try that, she'll slap me right on the spot.''
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   http://www.votecorzine.org
</P>
<P>
   http://www.bobfranks.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-09-07-00 1613 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000907.0090 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-07 16:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> High-Protein Corn Nets Food Prize  </HEADLINE>
By LISA J. ADAMS
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEXCOCO, Mexico (AP) -- For more than a decade, two scientists
labored in fields and laboratories to unlock the potential of corn,
boosting its nutritional value to help millions of malnourished
children around the world.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, their efforts were rewarded. Surinder K. Vasal and
Evangelina Villegas, scientists at the International Maize and
Wheat Improvement Center in Texcoco, won the World Food Prize for
their development of a corn containing 50 percent more usable
protein than normal corn. Their creation also yields 10 percent
more grain.
</P>
<P>
   The $250,000 prize, established by Nobel Peace Prize winner
Norman E. Borlaug, honors people who have made vital contributions
to improving food availability, quality and quantity. The prize was
announced in Des Moines, Iowa.
</P>
<P>
   ''This has tremendous potential to help alleviate the
malnutrition of children,'' Vasal said in a telephone interview
Thursday from Bangkok, Thailand, where he now works. ''Almost every
year, 12 million children die from malnutrition.''
</P>
<P>
   Villegas, a cereal chemist and the first woman to receive the
prize, demonstrated the fruits of the team's labor Wednesday during
a stroll through rows of experimental, high-protein cornstalks at
the research center an hour northeast of Mexico City.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's been really clear to us that there was a need to have
corn with better nutritional value,'' Villegas said.
</P>
<P>
   Many poor people in developing countries rely on corn as a
central part of their diet, even using it to wean their babies off
mothers' milk. Many are malnourished because most corn has little
protein.
</P>
<P>
   The new corn, called ''quality protein maize,'' contains the
same amount of total protein as the traditional variety. But it has
50 percent more lysine and tryptophan -- two essential amino acids
that are the building blocks of protein and that the body can use.
</P>
<P>
   The international center here conducted studies showing that
malnourished children in Colombia, Peru and Ghana who were put on
quality-protein-maize diets recovered, Villegas said.
</P>
<P>
   ''If they could eat a variety of foods for a well-balanced diet,
that would be great. But they don't have the resources to do that.
So our job is to improve the nutrition they have,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Today, 11 developing countries in Africa, Latin America and Asia
are growing the corn on 2.5 million acres of land and producing
seeds for future crops. Other countries are expected to begin
planting it in the next several years.
</P>
<P>
   Villegas and Vasal began their research in 1970 with a daunting
challenge.
</P>
<P>
   In their hands was opaque-2, a gene that had been found to
increase the nutritional value of corn. The problem was that no one
wanted it. The gene produced corn that was chalky-looking,
susceptible to disease and didn't produce a high enough yield to
make it worthwhile to plant.
</P>
<P>
   So Vasal, a corn breeder, headed into the cornstalks and began
crossbreeding thousands of varieties while Villegas labored in the
lab. By the mid-1980s, their methods produced a variety that looked
better and still upped the protein content.
</P>
<P>
   In the years since, they and other scientists have developed
varieties of the corn that adapt to different environments, produce
up to 10 percent more yield and can tolerate disease and drought.
</P>
<P>
   Quality protein maize also fattens animals faster using half as
much as regular corn, the researchers say. That means savings on
feed costs for poor farmers.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't think it will resolve all of the problems,'' Villegas
said. ''But it will help a special group, and this group is very
large.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-09-07-00 1615 </TRAILER>
