<BODY>
<HEADLINE> E-ZPass refunding mistaken $1 service charges  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   EAST BRUNSWICK, N.J. (AP) - E-ZPass is refunding $1 surcharges
it mistakenly assessed some of its customers, a transit official
said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Lynn Fleeger, a spokeswoman for the New Jersey Turnpike
Authority, the lead transit agency in the E-ZPass consortium, said
some customers who use the Garden State Parkway, the Atlantic City
Expressway or Port Authority of New York and New Jersey crossings
were mistakenly charged a $1 service fee.
</P>
<P>
   The problem, which she attributed to human error, involved
monthly statements. Customers who sign up for E-ZPass automatically
receive free monthly statements for the first six months. After
that, statements are issued every two months for free. If a
customer wants monthly statements after the first six months, a $1
charge would apply.
</P>
<P>
   Fleeger said an undetermined number of customers who did not
specifically request monthly statements were nonetheless hit with
the surcharge.
</P>
<P>
   Credits will be issued to their E-ZPass accounts, she said.
</P>
<P>
   The electronic toll collection service, which uses scanners and
electronic tags to identify specific vehicles and deduct the proper
toll from a prepaid account, is not yet available on the turnpike.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
