<BODY>
<HEADLINE> AMA Denounces Opening Records  </HEADLINE>
By JANELLE CARTER
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- A lawmaker's efforts to open to the public a
national databank that details doctors' malpractice history is
being denounced by the American Medical Association as retaliation
for physicians' support of a patients' bill of rights.
</P>
<P>
   House Commerce Committee Chairman Tom Bliley, R-Va., on Thursday
introduced the bill that opens the National Practitioners Databank.
The databank is now used only by the profession for the licensing
of doctors. It includes information on disciplinary actions as well
as medical malpractice payments.
</P>
<P>
   Bliley envisions making the information public so citizens can
access information about their doctors via the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   ''This bill provides patients with a fundamental new right -- the
right to more information about their doctors,'' Bliley said. The
legislation ''will give consumers the tools they need to make
informed decisions about their doctors.''
</P>
<P>
   But doctors' groups have cried foul, accusing Bliley of
targeting them because of their support to expand the rights of
managed care patients including the right to sue their health
maintenance organizations. The patients' rights bill is now stalled
in conference with House and Senate negotiators.
</P>
<P>
   ''Let me send a clear message to Rep. Bliley,'' said Dr. Thomas
Reardon, immediate past president of the American Medical
Association. ''We will not be distracted from our efforts to pass a
strong Patients' Bill of Rights and put an end to managed care
abuses.''
</P>
<P>
   Reardon said several states have already opened similar
information to the public. Systems operated by the states, Reardon
said, are a better way of disseminating information rather than a
national databank ''which contains mostly reports of legal
settlements that are not an indicator of physician quality or
competence.''
</P>
<P>
   ''Settling a lawsuit doesn't mean you're a bad physician,''
Reardon said.
</P>
<P>
   But Bliley aides complain that the state web sites focus only on
actions in that state and do not provide a comprehensive look at
problems doctors may have had in other parts of the country.
</P>
<P>
   Still, with just a few weeks left in the legislative session,
Bliley faces an uphill battle to pass the measure -- even within his
own party. A spokesman for Rep. Charles Norwood, a Georgia
Republican who is on the Commerce Committee, said the former
dentist would oppose the bill.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Greg Ganske, an Iowa Republican who is also a surgeon
sitting on Bliley's committee, said he has also concerns about the
measure.
</P>
<P>
   ''I have a concern. . . if that were made available to the
public it might not be interpreted accurately,'' Ganske said.
''Some of the best surgeons in my community had nuisance suits
settled out of court simply because insurance companies didn't want
to spend money on a defense.''
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: House Commerce Committee
http://www.house.gov/commerce/
</P>
<P>
   American Medical Association http://www.ama-assn.org/
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
