<HEADLINE> Commission Give Medals To Congress  </HEADLINE>
By JESSE J. HOLLAND
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- A survivor of the murder of Polish prisoners
of war by the Soviet secret police presented Congress with medals
Thursday for holding hearings in the 1950s that helped expose the
tragedy to the world.
</P>
<P>
   Reverend Monsignor Zdzislaw Peszkowski, adviser to the National
Katyn Memorial Committee, presented the Katyn Memorial Medal
Thursday to Rep. Ben Cardin, D-Md.
</P>
<P>
   Peszkowski said it took courage for American lawmakers to hold
hearings on the massacres while the Soviets were trying to keep it
secret. ''The United States' Congress had guts to do this,'' said
Peszkowski, a survivor of the massacre. ''Genocide cannot be
accepted.''
</P>
<P>
   ''We did it because it was a right thing to do,'' Cardin said.
</P>
<P>
   Soviet dictator Josef Stalin's secret police arrested some
26,000 Polish army and police officers and civilians after the Red
Army invaded Poland in September 1939.
</P>
<P>
   The secret police shot 15,000 Polish officers in the back of the
head in April and May 1940 and dumped many into common graves near
the Russian villages of Mednoye and Katyn, and the now-Ukrainian
city of Kharkov. Some 11,000 captured civilians, including doctors,
scientists and lawyers, also were killed secretly.
</P>
<P>
   The Katyn graves of some 4,000 officers were discovered by the
Nazis in 1943 and came to symbolize Soviet crimes against Poland.
</P>
<P>
   Congress held hearings on the massacre in 1951-52.
</P>
<P>
   The Kremlin doggedly denied responsibility for the murders until
1990, and they remain a scar on Polish-Russian relations.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
