<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-07 16:32 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dow Ends Down 52; Nasdaq Gains 84  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- High-tech stocks rebounded Thursday after a
two-day downturn, while blue chips fell following another spate of
corporate earnings warnings.
</P>
<P>
   The Nasdaq composite index ended the day up 84.31 at 4,097.65,
buoyed by the same stocks that investors couldn't wait to get rid
of earlier this week, according to preliminary calcuations.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow Jones industrial average was down 51.51 at 11,259.13 and
the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index was up 10.16 at 1,502.41.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is a continuation of the rotation the market has become
accustomed to,'' said Bob Streed, senior vice president at Northern
Trust in Chicago. ''The money seems to flow back and forth.
Yesterday, investors took their money out of technology and put
into blue chips. Today, they're taking it out of blue chips and
putting it back into technology.''
</P>
<P>
   Tech stocks had their best day so far in a trading week
abbreviated by the Labor Day holiday.
</P>
<P>
   Chipmaker Intel traded up $1.74 at $67.44 on the Nasdaq, after
tumbling for two days on an influential analyst's downgrade.
</P>
<P>
   Micron Technology, another chip maker that was downgraded by an
analyst on Wednesday, was up $4.75 to $73.50 on the Big Board.
</P>
<P>
   And Sun Microsystems rose $6.31 to close at $123.94 Thursday,
gaining back nearly all of its loss from Wednesday, when investors
bid the stock down from $124.75 to less than $118.
</P>
<P>
   Investor enthusiasm did not extend to blue chips, however, where
a mix of profit-taking and corporate warnings contributed to
investor flight. Shares of DuPont fell $5.19 to $41.81 after the
chemical company said earnings would be below expectations because
of decreased demand and higher costs.
</P>
<P>
   ''DuPont essentially said today it is going to have the same
kind of earnings as it did four years ago,'' said Mike Weiner, a
managing director at Banc One Investment Advisors in Columbus,
Ohio. ''Because DuPont is down, a lot of other companies are too.''
</P>
<P>
   Campbell Soup, Circuit City Stores and May Department Stores
also warned Thursday that their quarterly earnings would be flat or
below expectations. Circuit City fell 81 cents to $26.94 per share
and May was down $1.31 at $22.38. Shares of Campbell were up 25
cents at $25.13.
</P>
<P>
   Shares of Restoration Hardware dropped nearly 20 percent,
falling $1.19 at $4.81, after the home furnishings retailer said it
was in need of additional funding and had hired an investment bank
to help it find a new source of capital.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts have been warning investors to expect flat or lower
earnings because of the slowdown in economic growth. The Federal
Reserve has hiked interest rates six times since last summer, and
recent data suggest the economy is indeed slowing.
</P>
<P>
   Also Thursday, MP3 continued to decline, falling $1.69 -- or more
than 21 percent -- to $6.19. A federal judge ruled Wednesday that
MP3.com, which allows people to listen to songs over the Internet
but not download them to their computers, violated Universal's
copyrights.
</P>
<P>
   Advancing issues led decliners by a narrow margin on the New
York Stock Exchange, where volume came to 973.46 million shares,
compared to 992.46 million in the last session.
</P>
<P>
   The Russell 2000 index was up 6.48 at 542.80.
</P>
<P>
   Overseas, Japan's Nikkei stock average fell 0.60 percent.
Germany's DAX index was down 0.54 percent, Britain's FT-SE 100 was
down 0.08 percent, and France's CAC-40 was down 0.56 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   New York Stock Exchange: http://www.nyse.com
</P>
<P>
   Nasdaq Stock Market: http://www.nasdaq.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
