<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-07 16:32 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Art dealer Wildenstein surrenders, pleads guilty to menacing  </HEADLINE>
By SAMUEL MAULL
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) - Billionaire art dealer Alec Wildenstein, a
fugitive for two years, pleaded guilty Thursday to charges that he
pulled a gun on his wife after she caught him in bed with a
teen-ager.
</P>
<P>
   Wildenstein, 60, pleaded guilty to third-degree menacing, a
misdemeanor, in exchange for a conditional discharge. This means
that he is, in effect, on probation for a year and will not risk
jail if he is not arrested again.
</P>
<P>
   Manhattan Criminal Court Judge Suzanne Mondo also issued an
order of protection that bars the art dealer from contacting
Jocelyne Wildenstein, 55, whom he divorced in very public
proceedings two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Assistant District Attorney Cheryl Joseph told Mondo that the
ex-Mrs. Wildenstein had been told about the plea deal. ''She is
satisfied with this disposition,'' Joseph said. ''She, too, wishes
to put this behind her.''
</P>
<P>
   The charge to which Wildenstein pleaded was similar to one he
rejected shortly after he was arrested. Prosecutors offered then to
let him plead guilty and receive an ''adjournment in contemplation
of dismissal.'' This means he would have been released, and after
six months his case dismissed and his record sealed.
</P>
<P>
   The menacing charge stems from a confrontation early on Sept. 3,
1997, when Jocelyn Wildenstein and her two bodyguards found her
husband and a 19-year-old woman naked in a bedroom in their East
64th Street townhouse.
</P>
<P>
   Wildenstein said after his arrest that he leveled his licensed
.9 mm handgun at the men in the doorway because he did not know
them. He claimed that he did not see his wife at the time.
</P>
<P>
   As she accepted his guilty plea, Mondo asked Wildenstein, ''Did
you point a handgun at Jocelyne Wildenstein during an argument you
were having?''
</P>
<P>
   ''Yes,'' the defendant replied.
</P>
<P>
   Mondo lifted Wildenstein's gun license and told him he may not
apply for another for at least a year. She also ordered him to pay
a $60 court surcharge.
</P>
<P>
   Wildenstein is the chief operating officer of an art empire
mostly owned by his father Daniel and estimated to be worth more
than $5 billion. Their company owns the Wildenstein Gallery at 19
E. 64th St., and the Pace Wildenstein Gallery at 32 E. 57th St., as
well as art firms overseas.
</P>
<P>
   Wildenstein fled New York in September 1998, ignoring Criminal
Court Judge Paul Feinman's order to appear for trial on the
menacing charge. The art dealer was seen often in France in the
company of young women.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, State Supreme Court Justice Marylin Diamond gave his
wife an uncontested divorce on grounds of ''constructive
abandonment'' after she testified that Wildenstein had refused to
have sex with her since 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers in the divorce case would not discuss the financial
settlement. They refused to say whether Jocelyn Wildenstein got
more or less than the $140,000 a month temporary alimony she
received before the divorce.
</P>
<P>
   The divorced couple have a son and a daughter in their late
teens.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
