<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-07 16:40 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iraqi Leader Blasts U.S. at Summit  </HEADLINE>
By NICOLE WINFIELD
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS (AP) -- Iraq accused the United States on Thursday
of hijacking the work of the Security Council by orchestrating a
decade of crippling sanctions and said it held the United Nations
morally responsible for the resulting humanitarian catastrophe.
</P>
<P>
   In a speech to the U.N. Millennium Summit, Deputy Prime Minister
Tariq Aziz assailed the world body for bending to Washington's
will. He said efforts by the United Nations to better target the
sanctions to ease the suffering of innocent civilians were not
enough.
</P>
<P>
   ''Rather their use should be restricted,'' Aziz said. ''Also,
they should not be hostage ... to the will of the United States of
America, which hijacked the resolution on the lifting of sanctions
on Iraq from the Security Council to exploit it in the service of
its own interests and hostile policies.''
</P>
<P>
   Aziz was referring to a December resolution which promised to
suspend sanctions if Iraq cooperates with U.N. weapons inspectors,
who pulled out of Iraq in December 1998 ahead of U.S. and British
airstrikes.
</P>
<P>
   Iraq has said it will not allow the inspectors back into
Baghdad, arguing that it has already rid itself of weapons of mass
destruction and that Washington would find new reasons to keep the
measures even if it does cooperate with new arms monitors.
</P>
<P>
   The sanctions, in place since four days after Iraqi President
Saddam Hussein's 1990 invasion of Kuwait, bar the country from
trading with the rest of the world except through a limited
U.N.-sanctioned loophole.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. officials say Saddam's refusal to comply with the arms
inspectors is to blame for a economic collapse that has degraded
health and education in Iraq and left many of his citizens
dependent on U.N. food rations.
</P>
<P>
   Aziz's trip to New York for the summit marked the first time a
senior Iraqi leader had visited U.N. headquarters since the council
created a new arms inspection agency to replace the U.N. Special
Commission, which was tainted by allegations that its inspectors
had spied on Iraq on behalf of the United States.
</P>
<P>
   So far, Aziz has made no request to meet with Secretary-General
Kofi Annan during his visit, which is expected to last into next
week. Annan normally meets with every leader. Similarly Aziz hasn't
requested a meeting with the executive chairman of the new
inspection agency, Hans Blix, U.N. officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Aziz spoke just after Kuwait's foreign minister, Sheik Sabah
al-Ahmed al-Sabah, addressed the summit, pleading for support to
find the 605 Kuwaitis the country says are still missing from
Iraq's invasion, which prompted the 1991 Persian Gulf War.
</P>
<P>
   ''The sense of loss and frustration runs deep in the souls of
those families who continue to pin their hopes on the international
community to hold that regime accountable and to coerce it into
releasing those innocent victims or account for their
whereabouts,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   While Kuwait accuses Iraq of continuing to hold 605 Kuwaitis and
other nationals, Baghdad accuses Kuwait of failing to disclose
information about 1,150 Iraqis who disappeared during the fighting.
Both countries insist they are not holding any detainees.
</P>
<P>
   Iraq has withdrawn from the international committee looking into
missing persons, claiming it has not applied enough pressure on
Kuwait.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-09-07-00 1640 </TRAILER>
