<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-07 17:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Consumer group, AG fault HMOs for information flow to customers  </HEADLINE>
By JOEL STASHENKO
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) - Health maintenance organizations need the
prodding of the state attorney general's office to provide
customers with the basic information they're supposed to get, a
consumer group concluded Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Citizen Action said it sought the basic materials from all 29
HMOs in the state, and it gave 17 of them grades of ''A'' and one
an ''A-minus'' for supplying the mandatory information properly.
</P>
<P>
   Included in the group getting ''As'' were 13 of the 15 HMOs
which complied with a 1998 agreement with former Attorney General
Dennis Vacco to supply the basic materials to prospective enrollees
- member handbooks, contracts and directories of local health care
providers participating in that HMO.
</P>
<P>
   ''Our study found that the enforcement action the attorney
general took in 1998 worked,'' Citizen Action executive director
Richard Kirsch said.
</P>
<P>
   The group found that only one managed care company, the
Utica-based HMO Blue, signed the 1998 agreement but was not
complying with its terms.
</P>
<P>
   Of the 14 other HMOs in New York, Kirsch said the group gave
five ''As'' and four ''Cs'' for providing all or part of the
required information to customers. Five HMOs got ''Fs'' for
providing none of it: AmeriHealth Health Plan, Managed Health
(Health First), MagnaHealth of New York; United HealthCare of New
York and United HealthCare of Upstate, according to Citizen Action.
</P>
<P>
   Kirsch said he doubts whether the health care providers have
made a ''conscious decision'' not to provide prospective customers
with the information.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think they haven't made it an institutional priority to say,
'This is an important obligation and we ought to fulfill it,'''
Kirsch said.
</P>
<P>
   Leslie Moran of the New York Health Plan Association, which
represents HMOs in the state, said the Citizen Action report is
''very positive'' because it shows improvement in the overall
compliance rate. A 1998 survey by Vacco found that only half the
HMOs at that time were following the law, compared with only six
out of 29 in 2000 which did not provide any of the required
information.
</P>
<P>
   ''We think that the improvement demonstrates the health plans'
continued commitment to meeting the requirement of the managed care
law,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Moran also called the Citizen Action survey ''very subjective''
and argued that it was conducted with an ''anti-managed care
bias.''
</P>
<P>
   State Attorney General Eliot Spitzer, who beat Vacco in 1998,
said the Citizen Action study is important and that his office has
contacted those organizations which failed to provide the data. In
fact, Spitzer said he wants the 14 HMOs to enter into similar
agreements with the one Vacco made with the others in 1998, even
those which got ''As'' in the Citizen Action survey.
</P>
<P>
   It is crucial for consumers to know their rights when dealing
with HMOs, Spitzer said.
</P>
<P>
   ''If when we call a plan we cannot get the easiest, most simple
statements of what our rights are, of what our benefits are, then
we will never be able to make an informed decision,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Spitzer also said his office is making inquiries into how
several unidentified HMOs make decisions about which procedures
they will cover and which they will not cover. He declined to
elaborate.
</P>
<P>
   Citizen Action called for, and Spitzer endorsed, toughening
penalties for when HMOs are not providing consumers with adequate
information about the companies' services and patients' rights.
They said the current statute, which provides for the state Health
Department to fine offending companies up to $2,000 for a
violation, is not well defined.
</P>
<P>
   ''We need something that is a sharper tool,'' Kirsch said.
</P>
<P>
   John Signor, state Health Department spokesman, said the study
shows improvements in the information health plans are providing to
their customers.
</P>
<P>
   ''For those plans that need to do better, we will continuously
monitor them and cite them for any deficiencies and ensure that
they implement corrective actions,'' Signor said.
</P>
<P>
   HMOs participating in the 1998 agreement with Vacco getting
''As'' in the Citizen Action survey were: Aetna/U.S. Healthcare;
Cigna Healthcare; CDPHP; Community Blue; Healthnet/Empire
BlueChoice; HMO of CNY; Health Now; HIP; Independent Health Metro;
MDNY; North American Healthcare; Oxford and PHS.
</P>
<P>
   Those getting ''As'' which were not involved in the 1998
agreement were Independent Health of WNY; MHS (AmeriChoice); MVP;
PHP (Univera) and Preferred Care, Citizen Action said.
</P>
<P>
   Those getting ''Cs,'' all not parties to the 1998 agreement,
were: Blue Choice, GHI, Health Care Plan HCP (Univera) and Vytra.
</P>
<P>
   Citizen Action said it did not have enough information to give
Premier Health Plan a grade.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
