<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-07 17:20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russia: 33 Held As Bombing Suspects  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW (AP) -- At least 63 people were involved in deadly
apartment bombings across Russia a year ago, security officials
said Thursday as they presented a chart of how the explosives
allegedly were brought from Chechnya.
</P>
<P>
   Russia sent troops into the breakaway republic of Chechnya soon
after the four September 1999 bombings, which killed about 300
people. Chechen rebel leaders have denied responsibility for the
attacks.
</P>
<P>
   Two blasts occurred in Moscow, one in the southern city of
Volgodonsk and one in Buinaksk in the republic of Dagestan,
Chechnya's eastern neighbor.
</P>
<P>
   Security officials have taken 33 suspects into custody, said
Maj. Gen. Alexander Shagako, first deputy head of the fugitive
search department for the Federal Security Service, or FSB. They
have launched a search for 19 others, nine of whom are believed to
be abroad.
</P>
<P>
   Six suspects have been killed in fighting in Chechnya, Shagako
said at a press conference Thursday, Russian news agencies
reported.
</P>
<P>
   Five others have been charged with terrorism in the Buinaksk
bombing and their trial is pending.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the suspects are not Chechens but are from other ethnic
groups of southern Russia's Caucasus region, said FSB officer
Vladimir Kozlov.
</P>
<P>
   Shagako and colleagues at the FSB, the main successor to the
KGB, presented a chart of how they believe the explosives were
transported from Chechnya through several Russian cities and then
stored at locations in Moscow.
</P>
<P>
   It was unclear whether or when the remaining suspects would be
brought to trial. Police have said for months that they know who
was behind the bombings, but many high-profile crimes go unsolved
in Russia.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-09-07-00 1720 </TRAILER>
