<DOCNO> APW20000907.0106 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-07 17:20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Preschool Education Plans Touted  </HEADLINE>
By ANJETTA McQUEEN
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Better preschool reading instruction could
prevent some students from being wrongly tagged as
learning-disabled, Education Secretary Richard Riley said Thursday,
touting Democrats' early childhood and teacher-hiring initiatives.
</P>
<P>
   ''We do too much overlabeling; far too many children, especially
minorities and boys, are tracked into special education,'' Riley
said in his sixth annual back-to-school talk at the National Press
Club.
</P>
<P>
   He urged Congress to support increased funds for Head Start,
universal preschool for all 4-year-olds and other early childhood
plans touted by Vice President Al Gore's presidential campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans, meanwhile, offered their own plans for improving
literacy while criticizing the Democratic proposals.
</P>
<P>
   ''There are still those who believe in order to make something
work, you need only pour more money into it,'' said Rep. William
Goodling of Pennsylvania, who joined other Republican lawmakers in
backing Texas Gov. George W. Bush's plans to improve reading. ''Our
approach is to try to reform the programs and make them work.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush has proposed moving Head Start -- which provides education,
health screenings and family social services to 800,000 children --
from the Department of Health and Human Services to the Education
Department. Gore's plan, which would increase program funds more
than Bush's proposal, would leave Head Start where it is.
</P>
<P>
   One goal is to improve the nation's literacy, as Education
Department studies have shown that 44 million American adults,
about 21 percent of the population over 16, had only rudimentary
reading and writing skills.
</P>
<P>
   Both parties offered solutions.
</P>
<P>
   Riley, releasing the latest tally of teachers hired under a
Democrat plan, contended that 1.7 million children in grades K-3
are being taught in classes smaller than last year's, helping them
to become better readers that could turn them into better citizens.
</P>
<P>
   ''Our prison are full of illiterate young men,'' Riley said.
''There is a connection here that we need to understand and work
on.''
</P>
<P>
   Congressional Republicans countered that children are best
helped by offering parents the ability to take them out of
low-performing schools and send them to charter schools, educate
them at home or use vouchers to defray private and parochial school
tuitions.
</P>
<P>
   ''Parents should not be forced to send their child to a
deficient school,'' said Marian Miller, president of the National
Federation of Republican Women.
</P>
<P>
   The group said Bush's education plans would demand results of
schools by forcing them to show parents student test scores and
other measures of performance. In return for demonstrating
improvements, schools could spend federal dollars wherever they saw
fit, instead of being forced to allocate the money according to
federal rules.
</P>
<P>
   Bush would also spend $5 billion on a five-year plan to help all
children learn reading by third grade. Participating states would
be required to include phonics, train teachers and test students'
reading skills.
</P>
<P>
   Gore supports a $260 million-a-year grants program for
activities that would help students read by third grade.
</P>
<P>
   Congress is still working on the bulk of the nation's federal
education laws. Goodling said Thursday that House lawmakers will
consider a slate of programs designed to improve student reading.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   Education Department: http://www.ed.gov
</P>
<P>
   National Federation of Republican Women: http://www.nfrw.org
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
