<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Turkey Faces 'Cancer Plagues'  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANKARA, Turkey (AP) -- The government announced Thursday that it
planned to move residents of two central Anatolia communities to a
new location because the region's volcanic ash was believed to
cause cancer.
</P>
<P>
   The relocation follows a report by Turkish scientists
establishing a link between the high rate of lung cancer among the
inhabitants of Tuzkoy and Karain and the residents' constant
exposure to fibrous zeolite.
</P>
<P>
   Fibrous zeolite is a mineral fiber found in volcanic tuff, a
porous rock formed from volcanic ash.
</P>
<P>
   ''These villages have to be moved away,'' State Minister Sukru
Sina Gurel, the government spokesman, told reporters after a
Cabinet meeting. ''Fibrous zeolite is one of the most cancerous
substances and the frequency of cancer cases there is an indication
of that.''
</P>
<P>
   No figures were available on how many people were diagnosed with
or had died of cancer in the region.
</P>
<P>
   Gurel said the government had earmarked $5 million to move the
2,000 residents of Tuzkoy and the 600 from Karain to a safe
location nearby.
</P>
<P>
   Tuzkoy and Karain are close to Turkey's Cappadocia region,
popular with tourists, which is dotted with volcanic rock
formations and underground cities carved out by early Christians.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-09-07-00 1724 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000907.0109 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-07 17:26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> State finds four more infected crows in four additional counties  </HEADLINE>
By JOHN P. McALPIN
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRENTON, N.J. (AP) - Four more crows infected with the sometimes
fatal West Nile Virus have been found in four additional counties,
state health officials said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Health department spokesman Dennis McGowan also said 10 people
suspected of being infected with the mosquito-borne virus were
declared clear after test results showed no trace of the disease.
Tests on 11 other people are pending, he said.
</P>
<P>
   A Jersey City man is still New Jersey's only confirmed case of
human infection. State officials detailed his medical condition
Sept. 1.
</P>
<P>
   There have been seven cases of human infection in New York City
this year. The virus caused 62 human cases of encephalitis and
seven deaths in New York last year.
</P>
<P>
   Samples have been collected from 22 people with possible
symptoms who live in counties where the infected dead crows were
discovered.
</P>
<P>
   The latest infected crows were found in Burlington, Gloucester,
Hunterdon and Cape May counties, McGowan said.
</P>
<P>
   Across the state, 90 more crows were detected with the virus, he
said. The virus has been found in 14 counties.
</P>
<P>
   ''It indicates the virus is in birds across the state and our
surveillance efforts are working,'' McGowan said.
</P>
<P>
   Last year infected birds were found in 16 of the state's 21
counties.
</P>
<P>
   The health department announced in its weekly update on the
mosquito-borne virus that another 90 dead crows and two additional
mosquito pools have tested positive for West Nile.
</P>
<P>
   Altogether, the state said Thursday tests have found 585 dead
crows and one cockatiel collected around New Jersey were infected
with the virus, which first was identified in this country last
September.
</P>
<P>
   A horse in Cape May county also tested positive for West Nile,
state agriculture officials said Tuesday. The horse was euthanized.
</P>
<P>
   New Jersey asks all physicians and hospitals to test patients
who appear to have some symptoms of the mosquito-borne disease,
which include high fever and altered mental states.
</P>
<P>
   Residents are urged to protect themselves from mosquito bites by
wearing long clothing and insect repellant. People have been told
to clear all pools of standing water where mosquitoes breed.
</P>
<P>
   The virus is transmitted through the bite of mosquitoes that
have acquired it by feeding on an infected bird. Generally, it
causes flulike symptoms or no problems at all, but it can be
dangerous to young children, the elderly and anyone with a weak
immune system.
</P>
<P>
   All 21 counties in the state have increased mosquito-control
efforts, state officials said. Many of those programs include
spraying pesticides to kill the mosquitoes at various stages of
development.
</P>
<P>
   The 43-year-old Jersey City man began feeling ill Aug. 6,
suffering from symptoms that included a 100-degree fever. His
doctor notified the state after admitting the man to a hospital.
The unnamed man is recovering at home, according to state
officials.
</P>
<P>
   Infected birds have been found in Bergen (143), Burlington (1),
Cape May (1), Essex (70), Gloucester (1), Hudson(51), Hunterdon
(1), Mercer (1), Middlesex (125), Monmouth (79), Morris (8),
Passaic (43), Somerset (3) and Union (59) counties.
</P>
<P>
   So far this year, 1,211 crows have been tested.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
