<HEADLINE> Off-duty Tuckerton police officer dies in motorcycle wreck  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   BERKELEY TOWNSHIP, N.J. (AP) - A police officer who was a member
of a fatal accident investigation team was killed when his
motorcycle slammed into a school bus.
</P>
<P>
   Frank Podbielski, 36, traffic safety officer for the Borough of
Tuckerton, was off duty and riding his own motorcycle when it
struck a bus carrying Central Regional Middle School students at
Route 9 and Serpentine Drive East on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Podbielski, who was wearing a helmet, suffered head injuries and
was rushed to Jersey Shore Medical Center, where he was pronounced
dead 2&AMP;frac12; hours later, Patrolman Richard Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   None of the students was injured in the accident, which occurred
about 3:30 p.m. as the bus was taking students home from school.
The bus driver, Sandra Andrews of Bayville, was treated at
Community Medical Center in Toms River, Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   No charges had been filed as of late Thursday, Bush said. The
investigation is continuing.
</P>
<P>
   An 11-year veteran of the force, Podbielski was a member of a
countywide unit that investigated fatal accidents, said Tuckerton
Police Director James Territo. The unit is made up of traffic
safety officers from several municipalities.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's ironic. The guys he worked with on that unit turned out
to be the ones responding to his accident,'' said Territo.
</P>
<P>
   Podbielski is survived by his wife and an 8-year-old daughter.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're like a family here,'' said Territo, who oversees the
eight-member department. ''It hurts, it really does. We're
devastated, especially for the family.''
</P>
<P>
   The parents of children aboard the bus were notified about the
accident, according to Central Regional Schools Superintendent
Carol D'Zio. Guidance counselors and a school psychologist were to
be made available to the students, D'Zio said.
</P>
<P>
   A full police funeral is planned for Monday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
