<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-07 18:02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Polish Gov't Wants Disco Moved  </HEADLINE>
By BEATA PASEK
<TEXT>
<P>
   WARSAW, Poland (AP) -- A disco located in a former tannery where
Auschwitz concentration camp inmates worked and died should be
relocated, the Polish government urged Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The dance club opened last month after authorities in the
southeastern city of Oswiecim, the Polish name for the city of
Auschwitz, brushed aside protests and granted an investor a permit.
</P>
<P>
   Running a disco near where the Nazi camp was located during the
German occupation in World War II ''shows a lack of respect for
this tragic heritage,'' government spokesman Krzysztof Luft said in
a statement.
</P>
<P>
   Some 1.5 million people died in gas chambers, or of disease or
starvation, in Auschwitz.
</P>
<P>
   The permit for the disco had enraged camp survivors, including
Polish Foreign Minister Wladyslaw Bartoszewski, and from Jewish
organizations such as the Los-Angeles-based Simon Wiesenthal
Center.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the about 1,000 prisoners who worked in the tannery,
located about 1 mile from the main camp, died there. Historians say
the building was also used to store the property and hair of Jews
killed in the gas chambers.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, an entertainment company received permission to open
a disco in the former tannery, which is now privately owned, but
the provincial governor revoked the permit after protests.
</P>
<P>
   But city authorities issued a new permit in early August, saying
the application by the unidentified investor met the terms of the
city's development plans.
</P>
<P>
   ''We are told that the disco was opened in accordance with the
law, but, on the other hand, the government says it will do all it
can to close it,'' said Zdzislaw Bieniek, who represents the
disco's management.
</P>
<P>
   He said the government was telling Oswiecim residents ''You must
not have fun in this city. You must not live in a normal way in
this city.''
</P>
<P>
   Protests from Jewish organizations and other groups have also
help up plans to open a visitors' center with a cafeteria and book
store across from the main Auschwitz memorial.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-09-07-00 1802 </TRAILER>
