<HEADLINE> New Camden business administrator appointed  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   TRENTON, N.J. (AP) - The township manager in Willingboro has
been hired as the new business administrator in Camden, state
officials announced Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Norton N. Bonaparte Jr., will replace Preston Taylor, who is
retiring in October. Bonaparte will begin Oct. 2, said Jane M.
Kenny, commissioner of the state Department of Community Affairs.
</P>
<P>
   Bonaparte, of Willingboro, will earn $98,500 annually, said Tom
Damm, department spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   The state has been overseeing hiring, spending and contracts in
the financially ailing city since May.
</P>
<P>
   ''Norton has the background and leadership skills necessary to
promote sound management and fiscal integrity in the city of
Camden,'' said Kenny.
</P>
<P>
   ''He has impressed us with his professional accomplishments, his
academic credentials and his commitment to meeting the challenges
in Camden. He has a reputation for bringing people together to
solve problems.''
</P>
<P>
   Bonaparte said he wants to make positive changes in the city.
</P>
<P>
   ''I look forward to ensuring that the effective management of
the city's affairs contributes to the goal of economic recovery and
an improved quality of life for the citizens of Camden,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Bonaparte has been the Willingboro manager since 1995. He also
serves as a senior adjunct instructor at the School of Management
and Business at National-Louis University in McLean, Va.
</P>
<P>
   Bonaparte previously served as city manager in Glenarden, Md.,
and as a municipal official in Grand Rapids, Mich.
</P>
<P>
   He graduated from the Worcester Polytechnic Institute in
Massachusetts and holds a master's degree in public administration
from the Cornell University Graduate School of Management. He also
has taken doctoral courses in public administration at George Mason
University in Fairfax, Va.
</P>
<P>
   Camden City Council President Gwendolyn Faison said Bonaparte is
a good choice.
</P>
<P>
   ''I am confident he will work with the Council in the best
interests of the citizens of Camden,'' she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
