<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-07 18:49 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> PSC orders delay of Con Ed refunds  </HEADLINE>
By ANNY KUO
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) - The state's utility-regulating agency
decided Thursday to delay the refunds the state has ordered for
Consolidated Edison Co. ratepayers.
</P>
<P>
   The state Public Service Commission agreed to the state Consumer
Protection Board's request for the delay, saying that a pending
lawsuit brought by Con Ed challenging the refunds ''creates at
least some uncertainty'' over the issue.
</P>
<P>
   The Consumer board had asked for a one-month's delay in the
refunds, which were to have gone out Monday. The Public Service
Commission order Thursday did not specify a new date for the
refunds.
</P>
<P>
   Under a state law approved by the Legislature and Gov. George
Pataki earlier this year, about 3 million Con Ed customers are
supposed to get $162 million in refunds. For residential
ratepayers, the refunds would amount to about $14 in New York City
and $21 in Westchester County, Con Ed's service territory.
</P>
<P>
   A federal judge in Albany has scheduled oral arguments for Sept.
19 to hear Con Ed's challenge to the law. He has also set this
Friday as a deadline for the filing of papers into a preliminary
injunction requested by the utility asking that the refunds be
delayed until its claim against the state is decided.
</P>
<P>
   The utility will argue that the refund statute violates the U.S.
Constitution under a number of provisions, including equal
protection and due process clauses.
</P>
<P>
   ''Our concern has been to avoid potential confusion for our
customers down the road if the refund is overturned'' and the
utility would have to recollect the amount it refunded, Con Ed
spokesman Michael Clendenin said.
</P>
<P>
   The PSC said that while it assumes the court will uphold the
constitutionality of the law, the lawsuit nevertheless creates
concerns that a refund may backfire on ratepayers if the court
orders reimbursement for Con Ed.
</P>
<P>
   ''It is in the customer's best interest to delay the refund''
until the federal judge decides on whether to issue a temporary
injunction against the enforcement of the refund law, the PSC said.
</P>
<P>
   The PSC also argued that while state law requires the refunds,
it doesn't specify the timing or manner of the refund. It added
that more time is needed to solicit comments from additional
comments over this matter.
</P>
<P>
   State Assemblyman Richard Brodsky, a Westchester County Democrat
who has been attacking the Consumer Protection Board's request,
said the PSC's decision was ''stupefying.''
</P>
<P>
   ''They're in effect allowing Con Ed to keep close to $200
million in money which they wrongfully took from the pockets of the
average people,'' Brodsky said.
</P>
<P>
   Democratic U.S. Sen. Charles Schumer called the delay
''outrageous.''
</P>
<P>
   ''If mistakes are going to be swept under the rug with rate
increases, what incentive is there for any utility to do the job
right?'' Schumer said.
</P>
<P>
   State Attorney General Eliot Spitzer, who had also fought
against a delay, said the PSC's action basically ''grants Con Ed a
restraining order which even Con Ed had not sought from the
court.''
</P>
<P>
   ''We're looking at this order right now to see whether or not we
will go to court with this,'' Spitzer said.
</P>
<P>
   The refund money represents the cost to ratepayers of power Con
Ed has had to buy since February, when a nuclear power plant it
operates in Westchester County failed and went off line. State and
federal regulators have concluded that Con Ed should have seen the
problems at the Indian Point reactor coming and performed
maintenance to prevent the outage.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-09-07-00 1849 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000907.0138 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-07 18:50 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dow Ends Down 51; Nasdaq Gains 85  </HEADLINE>
By LISA SINGHANIA
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- High-tech stocks rebounded from a two-day
decline Thursday as investors, uneasy about a spate of corporate
earnings warnings, turned away from blue chip issues.
</P>
<P>
   The Nasdaq composite index ended the day up 85.01 at 4,098.35,
buoyed by the same stocks that investors had sold off earlier in
the week.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow Jones industrial average was down 50.77 at 11,259.87 and
the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index was up 10.26 at 1,502.51.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said the shift back to high-tech was more symptomatic
of overall uncertainty in the market, rather than any
bargain-hunting by investors.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is a continuation of the rotation the market has become
accustomed to,'' said Bob Streed, senior vice president at Northern
Trust in Chicago. ''The money seems to flow back and forth.
Yesterday, investors took their money out of technology and put
into blue chips. Today, they're taking it out of blue chips and
putting it back into technology.''
</P>
<P>
   Tech stocks had their best day so far in a trading week
abbreviated by the Labor Day holiday.
</P>
<P>
   Chipmaker Intel traded up $1.74 at $67.44 on the Nasdaq, after
tumbling for two days on an influential analyst's downgrade.
</P>
<P>
   Micron Technology, another chip maker that was downgraded by an
analyst on Wednesday, was up $4.75 to $73.50 on the Big Board.
</P>
<P>
   And Sun Microsystems rose $6.31 to close at $123.94, gaining
back nearly all of its loss from Wednesday, when investors bid the
stock below $118.
</P>
<P>
   The enthusiasm did not extend to blue chips, where a mix of
profit-taking and corporate warnings contributed to investor
flight. Shares of DuPont fell $4.88, or more than 10 percent, to
$42.13 after the chemical company said earnings would be below
expectations because of softening demand and higher costs.
</P>
<P>
   ''DuPont essentially said today it is going to have the same
kind of earnings as it did four years ago,'' said Mike Weiner, a
managing director at Banc One Investment Advisors in Columbus,
Ohio. ''Because DuPont is down, a lot of other companies are too.''
</P>
<P>
   Campbell Soup, Circuit City Stores and May Department Stores
also warned Thursday that their quarterly earnings would be flat or
below expectations. Circuit City fell 81 cents to $26.94 per share
and May was down $1.31 at $22.38. Campbell was up 25 cents at
$25.13.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts have been warning investors to expect flat or lower
earnings because of the slowdown in economic growth. The Federal
Reserve has hiked interest rates six times since last summer, and
recent data suggest the economy is indeed slowing.
</P>
<P>
   Restoration Hardware dropped nearly 20 percent, falling $1.19 at
$4.81, after the home furnishings retailer said it was in need of
additional funding and had hired an investment bank to help it find
a new source of capital.
</P>
<P>
   Also Thursday, MP3 continued to decline, falling $1.69 -- or more
than 21 percent -- to $6.19. A federal judge ruled Wednesday that
MP3.com, which allows people to listen to songs over the Internet
but not download them to their computers, violated Universal's
copyrights.
</P>
<P>
   Advancing issues led decliners by a narrow margin on the New
York Stock Exchange. Consolidated volume as 1.19 billion shares,
less than the 1.21 billion shares in the last session.
</P>
<P>
   The Russell 2000 index was up 6.50 at 542.82.
</P>
<P>
   Overseas, Japan's Nikkei stock average fell 0.60 percent.
Germany's DAX index was down 0.54 percent, Britain's FT-SE 100 was
down 0.08 percent, and France's CAC-40 was down 0.56 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   New York Stock Exchange: http://www.nyse.com
</P>
<P>
   Nasdaq Stock Market: http://www.nasdaq.com
</P>
</TEXT>
