<HEADLINE> Virus found in three more towns  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   HARTFORD, Conn. (AP) - The West Nile virus has been found in
three more towns, state environmental officials said Thursday
</P>
<P>
   Dead birds found in Bethany, Tolland and Trumbull tested
positive for the virus.
</P>
<P>
   So far this year, a total of 240 birds - nearly all crows - have
tested positive for the virus in 38 communities in the state. The
virus also has been found in three pools of bird-biting mosquitoes
in Stamford and Norwalk.
</P>
<P>
   West Nile is transmitted to humans by mosquitoes and can
sometimes lead to a deadly swelling of the brain.
</P>
<P>
   No human cases have been reported in the state and no spraying
is planned.
</P>
</TEXT>
