<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-07 18:51 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> With BC-NY--NY Senate  </HEADLINE>
By BETH J. HARPAZ
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) - Hillary Rodham Clinton is among 11 public
figures being honored Monday by the World Jewish Congress for
''helping bring about the various restitution settlements of the
last few years,'' according to WJC executive director Elan
Steinberg.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the first lady, the honorees include President
Clinton, former Sen. Alfonse D'Amato, city Comptroller Alan Hevesi,
and several Clinton administration and Israeli government
officials.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the honorees were actively involved in negotiations with
governments and financial institutions that resulted in the
allocation of $9 billion in restitution for Nazi victims.
</P>
<P>
   Steinberg said Hillary Clinton was being included because she
arranged a meeting between the president and WJC president Edgar
Bronfman in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   At the time, Bronfman was scheduled to testify at hearings being
held by D'Amato, who was then chairman of the Senate Banking
Committee. Bronfman asked the first lady to help get the president
involved to ensure that efforts would be bipartisan. ''Within 24
hours, she arranged the meeting,'' Steinberg said.
</P>
<P>
   Bronfman was recently made a co-chair of Hillary Clinton's
Senate campaign advisory committee on Jewish issues. She is
fighting hard for Jewish votes in New York in a tight race against
Rep. Rick Lazio, a Long Island Republican.
</P>
<P>
   Asked whether it was appropriate to honor the first lady
alongside others who may have played larger, more public roles in
the restitution effort, especially given the circumstances of her
current campaign, Steinberg defended the dinner, saying: ''Other
people want to inject politics into this dinner. This is a World
Jewish Congress 'thank you' to public officials who have brought
about this revolution in the recognition in the rights of those who
were robbed.''
</P>
<P>
   Jonathan Greenspun, the Lazio campaign's liaison on Jewish
affairs, noted that Lazio, who is not among the honorees,
contributed to restitution efforts through his position on the
House Banking Committee. He introduced a bill that extended by a
year the life of a commission investigating what happened to assets
that came into the possession of the U.S. government.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton spokesman Howard Wolfson said the first lady was proud
to be recognized and was looking forward to the dinner.
</P>
<P>
   Abe Foxman, a Holocaust survivor who heads the Anti-Defamation
League, said that ''regardless of the minor controversies as to
whether everybody being honored is equally worthy, the fact is that
we would not be at this stage on this issue - i.e. closure or close
to closure - if it hadn't been for Edgar Bronfman, the WJC and many
if not most of the people who are being honored. Hopefully it will
bring closure for everybody on the issues.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
