<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-07 18:52 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Florida' Bullard: Not Just a Player  </HEADLINE>
By EDDIE PELLS
<TEXT>
<P>
   GAINESVILLE, Fla. (AP) -- In an era when the term
''student-athlete'' seems to draw more snickers than straight
faces, guys like Thaddeus Bullard remind football fans that there's
still hope.
</P>
<P>
   The Florida defensive end is a member of two service
organizations on campus. He's the student body vice president. He
sometimes appears at three or four public speaking engagements a
week. He has volunteered to teach children to read and the disabled
to swim. He graduated in four years and is currently working on a
master's degree in higher education.
</P>
<P>
   ''Sometimes, it kills me,'' said Bullard, who will start
Saturday when No. 8 Florida plays Middle Tennessee. ''I've enjoyed
every minute. The University of Florida is by far ... the greatest
thing I've ever experienced.''
</P>
<P>
   He came oh-so-close to having the experience taken away.
</P>
<P>
   Two weeks into fall practice of his freshman year, the NCAA
declared him an academic non-qualifier, invalidating a score from
one of his core courses in high school.
</P>
<P>
   The decision was disputed -- some say it was based on a
typographical error from a teacher's grade book. Nobody from the
NCAA ever explained it to Bullard.
</P>
<P>
   It was a degrading and deflating experience. Bullard felt he was
unfairly lumped into a group of athletes widely perceived to be
working the system for a free education and another chance for
glory on the football field.
</P>
<P>
   ''I felt like they felt that this was just another black
athlete, or athlete in general, trying to skate through the
system,'' Bullard said. ''Does that happen? Yes. But there are a
lot of times the athletes bust their tails. ... Those type of
things are very disturbing to me.''
</P>
<P>
   The appeals process didn't turn out quite the way Bullard hoped.
His only option was to enroll in spring semester and try to crowd a
year's worth of classes into the spring and two summer sessions.
</P>
<P>
   He did that to make himself eligible for the 1997 season. Coach
Steve Spurrier recognized the achievement by giving Bullard jersey
No. 11, the same one Spurrier wore as a Heisman Trophy winner in
the 1960s.
</P>
<P>
   Then, Bullard one-upped himself, graduating in four years, and
earning back the year of eligibility he lost in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   This year, he has switched his jersey to No. 90 because ''coach
Spurrier said I didn't look like a defensive end wearing No. 11.''
</P>
<P>
   And for all the success Bullard has enjoyed off the field, he
has yet to really look like the defensive end the Gators recruited
back in 1995. In his first three years, the 6-foot-4, 253-pound
blue-chip recruit produced only 2.5 sacks in 34 games.
</P>
<P>
   ''He's had an excellent academic career here,'' Spurrier said.
''Hopefully, he'll finish it off with a good football career.''
</P>
<P>
   Not that anything could take away his other accomplishments. His
time at Florida has been a success regardless of the stats.
</P>
<P>
   ''Instead of dwelling on the disappointments, he moved on,''
athletic director Jeremy Foley said.
</P>
<P>
   Foley skipped Florida's national-championship celebration in
1996 to attend a meeting and fight for Bullard's eligibility.
</P>
<P>
   ''I would have done that for anyone,'' Foley said. ''But there's
no doubt, watching Thad progress has been fun to watch. He saw the
silver lining.''
</P>
<P>
   Bullard says the NCAA rejection didn't necessarily motivate him
to make the most of his time at Florida. He concedes, however, that
his success has probably sent a message to the anonymous faces at
the NCAA who nearly derailed him.
</P>
<P>
   ''That just makes my point more valid,'' Bullard said. ''I can
come to college and be successful. It's not up to the NCAA. When it
all comes down to it, if a kid wants to go and get a good education
he's going to go get it, regardless of whether you allow them in
school this year, the next year or the year after.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-09-07-00 1852 </TRAILER>
