<HEADLINE> Denver's Davis Might Play Falcons  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENVER (AP) -- Still nursing a sprained left ankle, running back
Terrell Davis gave the Denver Broncos reason to be believe he would
play Sunday against the Atlanta Falcons.
</P>
<P>
   Davis was held out of practice Thursday for the second straight
day, but he reported improvement to his ankle and graduated from
walking to jogging.
</P>
<P>
   ''My gut feeling is he'll be able to play,'' Denver coach Mike
Shanahan said. ''I could see he was jogging a little bit out there
on the field, so that's a good sign.''
</P>
<P>
   The Broncos were hoping Davis would return to practice Friday.
Regardless of whether he practices, his status for Sunday likely
will be made in the hours before the game.
</P>
<P>
   ''Right now, he feels there's a good chance,'' Shanahan said.
</P>
<P>
   Davis, who missed the final 12 games of 1999 with a torn knee
ligament, ran for 34 yards on nine carries in Denver's
season-opening loss to the St. Louis Rams on Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   He left the game in the second quarter and did not return.
</P>
<P>
   Backup running back Olandis Gary later tore the anterior
cruciate ligament in his right knee and is out for the season,
leaving rookie Mike Anderson in line to start if Davis is unable to
play.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to Davis, linebacker Al Wilson (separated shoulder)
and wide receiver Ed McCaffrey (groin) did not practice Thursday.
Wilson is listed as doubtful, but McCaffrey could return Friday.
</P>
