<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-07 19:26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sydney Weather Forecast Looking Up  </HEADLINE>
By LARRY SIDDONS
<TEXT>
<P>
   SYDNEY, Australia (AP) -- Athletes huddled around space heaters
and piled on extra blankets, trying to avoid the chill that has the
city bundled up a week before the Summer Games.
</P>
<P>
   After a raw, cold Thursday with the high temperature 10 degrees
below the normal of just under 70, a storm blew through and brought
a sunny dawn Friday and a forecast high of 72. But few were about
to head for Bondi Beach with sunscreen and surfboards.
</P>
<P>
   Winds were up, with gale-force gusts expected, and the forecast
through Monday called for highs hovering in the upper 60s under
sunny skies.
</P>
<P>
   In this land of sun and fun, central heating is not necessarily
included in even the newest homes, and athletes at the just-opened
Olympic Village have to rely on electric-powered space heaters for
warmth.
</P>
<P>
   Each bed comes topped with a thick quilt, or doona, that's
supposed to be as warm as two blankets. But Olympic organizers were
scrambling to provide another 3,900 blankets after some of the
athletes and coaches complained of the cold.
</P>
<P>
   ''We've asked for some more blankets because it's very cold in
some of the apartments,'' said Hajera Kajee, the deputy leader of
South Africa's team. ''There are heaters, but there are no plugs.''
</P>
<P>
   Even athletes from normally colder climes were caught off guard
by the chill.
</P>
<P>
   ''I thought Australia would be sunny and pretty hot, lots of
sand and kangaroos,'' said Dante Craig, a boxer in the 137-pound
class from Cincinnati. ''It's cold, and I haven't seen a kangaroo
yet.''
</P>
<P>
   Spring officially started here Sept. 1, about three weeks
earlier than the rest of the Southern Hemisphere. It may be winter
elsewhere below the equator but, hey, this is Australia, where the
lifeguard is an icon and the perfect tan sometimes seems to be a
national birthright.
</P>
<P>
   It actually was a mild winter, despite windy, chilly conditions
at the Australian Olympic track trials two weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   And this week started nice, with sunny skies and temperatures in
the upper 60s and 70s, a bit above normal. Locals kept telling
skeptical newcomers they had just missed gorgeous weather, somewhat
like telling a fisherman with an empty creel that he should have
seen the ones they were landing yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   ''It got hot the last couple days,'' Craig said. ''But it has
been real chilly. I'm from Cincinnati, so it doesn't bother me.''
</P>
<P>
   At the media village, where about half the expected 5,858 guests
had checked in by Thursday afternoon, residents were sticking
rolled-up towels at the bottom of doorsills to keep the cold out.
</P>
<P>
   ''We usually have glorious weather here,'' said Geoffrey Bennun,
the village's manager. ''It's better to have rain now than after
the 15th,'' the first day of the games.
</P>
<P>
   ''Sure, we have to contend with the fact that it's a little bit
cold,'' Bennun said. ''But we expect the Canadians to be sturdy,
the Norwegians to be sturdy, the New Yorkers to be sturdy.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
