<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-07 19:28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Appeals court says executives did not profit before recall  </HEADLINE>
By JONATHAN POET
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA (AP) - A federal appeals court, agreeing with a
lower court judgment, ruled Thursday that American Home Products
executives did not benefit from inside information about problems
with two popular diet drugs that were later recalled.
</P>
<P>
   The class-action lawsuit by shareholders claimed that executives
of the Madison, N.J.-based company made a profit of nearly $25
million from stock sales while failing to disclose problems with
one of the ingredients of fen-phen.
</P>
<P>
   The 3rd U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals agreed with a federal
district judge, who ruled in February 1999 that shareholders did
not show that the stock sales by executives were unusual or
suspicious.
</P>
<P>
   The class-action lawsuit alleged that AHP knew of a Mayo Clinic
study linking fen-phen to potentially fatal heart valve damage in
March 1997, but did not tell investors. The drugs were withdrawn
from the market in September 1997.
</P>
<P>
   The appeals court ruled that AHP's silence on the Mayo Clinic
study was not misleading, since it did not have a duty under law to
inform shareholders. The judges also noted that AHP executives sold
more stock in 1996 than in 1997, the year the drugs were withdrawn
from the market, and that the trades ''were not suspicious in
scope.''
</P>
<P>
   Marian P. Rosner, a lawyer for the shareholders, said she had
not seen the decision, but that her team would consider an appeal.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think it's erroneous. I feel sorry for the shareholders,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   Messages left for American Home Products' representatives were
not immediately returned.
</P>
<P>
   American Home Products made fenfluramine, half of the fen-phen
diet drug combination. The company sold the combination under the
brand name of Pondimin and also made Redux, a chemical cousin. The
second drug in Redux, phentermine, was not linked to heart valve
problems.
</P>
<P>
   Two weeks ago, a federal judge approved a $3.75 billion national
settlement of health claims stemming from the diet drug
combination. Under the settlement, fen-phen users would get up to
$1.5 million, though most would get far less, depending on their
level of injury and how long they took the drugs. The settlement
also includes money for future medical monitoring.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
