<HEADLINE> U.N. summit plus Met gala plus MTV Awards equals monster NYC gridlock </HEADLINE>
By DEEPTI HAJELA
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) - Traffic became a standing-room only affair in
parts of midtown Manhattan on Thursday as the United Nations'
Millennium Summit, a grand party for world leaders at the
Metropolitan Museum of Art and the annual MTV Video Awards combined
to cause hair-raising snarls.
</P>
<P>
   Protests near the U.N. - against American interference in Haiti,
human rights abuses in China and slavery in Sudan among scores of
other world issues - added to the usual bumper-to-bumper rush hour
mess.
</P>
<P>
   Several police officers on traffic detail described the volume
as ''Christmas time'' heavy.
</P>
<P>
   Periodic closures of the FDR Drive and streets and avenues on
the East Side near U.N. headquarters forced commuters there to find
new routes. And near Radio City Music Hall, where stars were
arriving for the MTV Video Music Awards, Sixth Avenue was shut down
to drivers - and in some spots, even to pedestrians.
</P>
<P>
   An evening gala for world leaders at the Metropolitan Museum of
Art, hosted by President Clinton, was bound to add to the tie-ups,
as scores of motorcades headed uptown.
</P>
<P>
   Mayor Rudolph Giuliani, who said he is honored that the city is
host to the summit, has at the same time complained about the
event's psychic and financial cost - traffic and heavy security for
the more than 150 world leaders who have gathered for the three-day
event.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, Giuliani sent a letter to President Clinton asking
that the federal government reimburse the city $25 million for its
expenses, ranging from overtime for the police and fire departments
to sanitation costs.
</P>
<P>
   ''New York's unique place in the world of international
diplomacy is a great honor, but it simultaneously imposes a
tremendous security burden, at a significant cost to New York City
taxpayers,'' Giuliani wrote. ''I am writing to ask you to take
action to guarantee that the city will receive funding for all
costs of providing security for foreign dignitaries and
international events, now and in the future.''
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani, who has long complained about foreign diplomats who do
not pay their city parking tickets, also released a list of the
biggest scofflaws, which was headed by Russia.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1995, Russian diplomats have received 63,834 parking
tickets and owe the city $7.2 million. Following Russia is
Indonesia, which owes $2.6 million; Egypt, which owes $2.4 million;
and Nigeria, which owes $2 million.
</P>
<P>
   Said Giuliani: ''If we can teach all of the countries that
belong to the United Nations to pay their parking tickets, which is
to meet their lawful obligation to the host country, maybe then
they would understand the rule of law.''
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani refused to attend Clinton's reception at the
Metropolitan Museum, saying some of the leaders attending ''have
murdered a lot of people.''
</P>
<P>
   He has been particularly critical of Palestinian leader Yasser
Arafat and Cuban President Fidel Castro, who he called ''a
murderer'' earlier this week. Cass0448-----
r s BC-SOC--EU-Transfers     09-07 0174
BC-SOC--EU-Transfers,0173
EU, FIFA, UEFA working on European soccer transfer system
</P>
<P>
   STRASBOURG, France (AP) - Players for European soccer clubs
won't be granted unchecked free agency under a new transfer system.
</P>
<P>
   ''The European Commission in no way intends to ... create a
situation to allow a player unilaterally to renege on a contract,''
EU Sports Commissioner Viviane Reding said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   European Union officials also chastised FIFA and UEFA, the
sport's world and European governing bodies, for letting the
current player movement rules get out of hand.
</P>
<P>
   After the EU's executive commission threatened to outlaw the
current soccer transfer system, FIFA agreed to revamp the system,
making a proposal Wednesday. The new plan included scrapping
transfer fees for players older than 24.
</P>
<P>
   Players in European leagues are not required to serve out their
contracts with a club if another team is willing to pay a transfer
fee to hire them.
</P>
<P>
   The EU stand raised fears that players would be able to leave
clubs at will.
</P>
</TEXT>
