<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-07 19:44 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Greek Victims Remember Quake  </HEADLINE>
By ELENA BECATOROS
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATHENS, Greece (AP) -- A dried wreath lies atop the rubble of a
factory complex that crumbled in seconds during a devastating
earthquake a year ago. A few yards away is a more bitter -- and some
say, more fitting -- memorial to the 38 people killed there.
</P>
<P>
   The sun-parched flowers commemorate the 143 people who died in
the 5.9 magnitude quake Sept. 7, 1999. The Ricomex factory had the
largest single death toll of the disaster.
</P>
<P>
   But a plain white marble monument, with a plaque reading
''Memorial of Disgrace'' above the names of the victims, stands as
a reminder of those who died at the household products plant.
</P>
<P>
   Relatives of those killed blame shoddy construction for the
collapse and are bitterly angry at Greek authorities for the slow
pace of an investigation into the factory's builders.
</P>
<P>
   ''The 'Disgrace' is for the state authorities who have been
silent until now, and for those who built this wreck,'' said
Stefanos Psiridis, whose sister Ioanna was killed in the collapse.
</P>
<P>
   As a sign of respect, shops remained closed Thursday in some of
the areas hardest hit last year. About 80 relatives clad in black,
many of them weeping, gathered at the Ricomex monument for a
memorial service.
</P>
<P>
   Most descended into the large crater, left when the rubble was
cleared, to lay flowers on the remaining wreckage. One wreath bore
the word ''murdered'' across the front.
</P>
<P>
   In the quake's aftermath, Greek authorities pledged to
investigate the construction quality of buildings that went down.
But investigations have been slowed by missing documents and other
problems.
</P>
<P>
   The quake damaged 70,000 buildings around the capital, leaving
about 100,000 people homeless. The factory was located near the
quake epicenter in Athens' northern suburbs.
</P>
<P>
   ''It was a great trial for our country, which struck many people
and had many detrimental side-effects,'' government spokesman
Tilemahos Hitiris said. ''One year later, many things remain to be
done.''
</P>
<P>
   ''An earthquake is a natural disaster. It is self-evident that
one can't press a button for everything to become perfect, as they
would want from one minute to the next,'' Hitiris added.
</P>
<P>
   Resettling and compensating quake victims and repairing damage
will cost $270 million, Planning Minister Costas Laliotis said.
</P>
<P>
   ''Although much has been done, there remains much more to do,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Earthquakes last summer in both Turkey and Greece -- and the
mutual aid offered by the two neighbors -- have been credited with
helping warm relations between the two regional rivals. More than
17,000 people were killed in the Aug. 17, 1999, quake in
northwestern Turkey.
</P>
<P>
   But the diplomatic advances mean little to those still living in
temporary housing in Athens.
</P>
<P>
   About 6,000 families are staying in converted containers in
state camps. Although the government is providing low-interest
loans to help quake victims rebuild their homes, many complain that
the amounts are small and procedures to obtain them long-winded and
bureaucratic.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's hard and they ask for so many papers, so we gave up and
we're just funding the repairs ourselves,'' said Vasilis Kataras,
who said he had chosen to remain in his severely damaged home until
he began repairs a month ago.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's not possible to rebuild just with the money that they
give,'' said Mina Tordatzi as she watered plants in the garden she
has created outside her container home.
</P>
<P>
   Tordatzi, her husband and three grown children spent three
months living in a tent camp after the quake before they were moved
to the converted container camp in the Athens suburb of Menidi.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's OK living here -- better than living in those tents, in
that mess that we were in,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the homeless families seem resigned to the idea that
they'll be living in the camp for many more months. Well-tended
gardens have appeared, and raised wooden porches with red tile
roofs have been added to the fronts of the plain containers.
</P>
<P>
   The family of Despina Iliadou built an extension to theirs to
create a living room.
</P>
<P>
   ''I took all my plants from my house and brought them here,''
said Iliadou, proudly displaying her tidy home. ''I can't stand
wretchedness.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
