<BODY>
<HEADLINE> School year in limbo as Buffalo teachers strike  </HEADLINE>
By CAROLYN THOMPSON
<TEXT>
<P>
   BUFFALO, N.Y. (AP) - School district and union officials set to
work plotting their next moves after a surprise teachers' strike
threw the young school year into limbo.
</P>
<P>
   As teachers walked picket lines Thursday, a state mediator met
individually with both sides and union officials delivered a
counter offer to the Board of Education's latest contract proposal.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly before 8 p.m. Thursday, District Superintendent Marion
Canedo canceled classes for Friday, saying she had not heard
anything from the union and wanted to give parents and guardians as
much time as possible to prepare for another day without school.
</P>
<P>
   Board President Paul Buchanan said the sides were not as far
apart as it might appear.
</P>
<P>
   ''That's why the strike is so surprising,'' he said. ''We're
down to maybe four or five unresolved issues after bargaining now
for half a year.''
</P>
<P>
   Buffalo Teachers Federation President Philip Rumore had a much
different take.
</P>
<P>
   ''Their proposal was so far away from what's acceptable,'' he
said. ''It's absolutely mind-boggling they should be able to think
there wouldn't have been a strike.''
</P>
<P>
   The two sides remained at odds over wages, health care
concessions, and a provision to contract with outside social
agencies.
</P>
<P>
   The strike was called less than an hour before Thursday's start
of school, forcing the cancellation of what would have been the
second day of classes for 47,000 students.
</P>
<P>
   Thousands of children and their parents were already out the
door on the way to school and work and parents were left scrambling
to find child care.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's just frustrating to have 20 minutes notice,'' said Audrey
Sanders, an architect who took her three children to work with her.
</P>
<P>
   School buses already en route were turned around and returned
the children home. In about 50 cases where no adults were home,
young children were brought to schools and spent the day under the
supervision of administrators, Buchanan said.
</P>
<P>
   ''There were no lost children, no injuries, there was no
violence,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Under state law which prohibits teachers from striking, the
district's 3,800 teachers stand to lose two days pay for each day
on strike. They also could face jail time for defying a court
injunction obtained by the Board of Education forbidding the
walkout. A hearing on the injunction is scheduled for Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ''This move is something that we've been forced into,'' Rumore
said. ''This is not something that we do lightly.''
</P>
<P>
   The teachers' latest contract expired in June 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Rumore said teachers were insulted by the district's latest
four-year offer that included no pay raise the first year and
raises of 2 percent in each of the subsequent years.
</P>
<P>
   District officials countered that the union did not take into
account built-in pay increments of 1 to 5 percent that would come
on top of the across-the-board raises.
</P>
<P>
   ''Our settlement package is right in the middle of what
districts in western New York are settling for,'' Buchanan said.
''The total average is 3.9 percent a year for four years and the
average in western New York is 3.5 percent to 4.5 percent.''
</P>
<P>
   The union is seeking raises closer to 4.9 percent, he said.
</P>
<P>
   While the strike was citywide on Thursday, Rumore left open the
possibility that it would be scaled back to selected schools in the
future.
</P>
<P>
   But Buchanan said without a complete halt to the strike, schools
would remain closed.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's the only safe and responsible way to guarantee the safety
of the schoolchildren,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Buffalo teachers struck illegally for 13 days in 1976.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-09-07-00 2002 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
