<DOCNO> APW20000907.0161 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-07 20:07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Judge throws out challenge to city's parade rules  </HEADLINE>
By SAMUEL MAULL
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) - A Manhattan judge threw out a petition Thursday
by organizers of Saturday's Labor Day Parade who challenged the
city's planned enforcement of rules that ban cooking at parades.
</P>
<P>
   State Supreme Court Justice Bruce Allen said it was unfortunate
that the city did not mention the rule enforcement issue earlier,
given the parade's history and the three months of negotiations for
the parade permit.
</P>
<P>
   ''However,'' Allen said, ''it does not follow that the city can
be enjoined from enforcing existing regulations.'' The judge also
noted that city officials never told the parade planners that
cooking would be allowed.
</P>
<P>
   The Central Labor Council, a coalition of about 500 unions, will
appeal Allen's decision on Friday, union lawyer Douglas Menagh
said.
</P>
<P>
   Sunny Mindel, spokeswoman for the mayor, issued a statement:
''We applaud the judge's decision which is in the best interests of
the city's public safety. We're sure this will not at all impede on
the event or its success, and they will have another great
parade.''
</P>
<P>
   The council had complained that the unions stood to lose
hundreds of thousands of dollars because the city, after three
months of talks, did not tell parade planners until Aug. 30 about
the parade rule enforcement.
</P>
<P>
   Ted Jacobsen, secretary of the Labor Council, said in an
affidavit that the unions had spent money on food, including hot
dogs, hamburgers, buns, sweet rolls and drinks, and on cooking and
refrigeration equipment.
</P>
<P>
   The council argued that the city's new rules were not legally
enacted, and that the old rules had not been enforced in past years
and therefore the city should not be allowed to start enforcing
them now.
</P>
<P>
   ''We are not against changing the rules,'' the council said in a
statement. ''Our main argument is that rules should not be changed
after all preparations are completed.''
</P>
<P>
   City lawyers contended that the city is only enforcing existing
laws, but Allen said some of the rules - such as the limit on the
height of floats - appeared to be new. He also noted that the law
has exceptions to the ''open-flame'' rule.
</P>
<P>
   In dismissing the council's petition, Allen said expects that
''existing general regulations, rather than special rules, are to
be enforced.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-09-07-00 2007 </TRAILER>
