<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-07 20:45 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Gadhafi: US-Libya Ties Normalizing  </HEADLINE>
By MAAMOUN YOUSSEF
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAIRO, Egypt (AP) -- Libyan leader Moammar Gadhafi expressed
optimism Thursday that his country's strained relations with the
United States could be eased and normal ties restored.
</P>
<P>
   ''I believe there is nothing which prevents the resuming or
normalizing of relations between the two countries,'' Gadhafi told
CNN in a live interview monitored in Cairo.
</P>
<P>
   Still considered a sponsor of terrorism by the United States,
Libya has made steps in recent years to rebuild its international
status. Last year, it handed over suspects in the 1988 bombing of
Pan Am Flight 103, and in recent weeks the country was key in
negotiating the release of six Western hostages held in the
Philippines.
</P>
<P>
   ''It is now a new era,'' Gadhafi said. America should
''reconsider its imperialist approach, because it does not fit with
the new era and it will fail in the end,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   Gadhafi sharply attacked the United Nations when he was asked
about being absent from the worldwide U.N. summit ongoing in New
York.
</P>
<P>
   ''Do you expect me to cross the Atlantic Ocean to speak for five
minutes? The U.N. is not real now; when it is reformed, we would
think of talking there,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Relations between the United States and Libya deteriorated
during the 1970s and 1980s over accusations that Gadhafi was aiding
terrorists. The United States imposed trade sanctions against Libya
in 1986, blaming the North African nation for a bomb blast that
killed three people at a West Berlin disco frequented by U.S.
servicemen.
</P>
<P>
   Gadhafi's adopted daughter was killed when the United States
bombed Tripoli and the port city of Benghazi in retaliation for the
disco blast.
</P>
<P>
   A U.S. Congress research service report last month said Libya
appeared to have sharply reduced its support of international
terrorist groups, and the United States is considering lifting an
American travel ban after a fact-finding visit to Libya in April by
a State Department delegation.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
