<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Judge rules sled dogs must be returned to owner  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   QUEENSBURY, N.Y. (AP) - A judge has ruled that 13 sled dogs must
be returned to the couple that was acquitted last month of
neglecting dozens of their dogs.
</P>
<P>
   The Society for the Prevention of Cruelty to Animals of Upstate
New York has vowed to fight the return of the 13 dogs to Mark and
Lisa Labrecque until the couple pays nearly $29,000 in boarding and
medical fees owed the SPCA's shelter for boarding the dogs since
Jan. 24.
</P>
<P>
   The SPCA seized 45 dogs from the couple's home after five
puppies were found dead on their property. The Labrecques forfeited
possession of all but the 13 dogs remaining in the SPCA's shelter.
On Aug. 21, a jury found them innocent of animal cruelty and the
Labrecques filed suit against the SPCA, saying it has no right to
hold the dogs now that the criminal case has ended.
</P>
<P>
   Warren County Judge John Austin agreed, ruling that since the
jury decided the Labrecques did not violate the state Agriculture
and Markets Law, as the SPCA claimed, the same law must be used to
return the dogs.
</P>
<P>
   The lawyer for the SPCA, who said he would seek a stay to keep
the dogs at the SPCA, argued that the animal protective
organization had a valid lien against the Labrecques and was hold
the dogs as collateral. Tucker Stanclift also said the matter is
now civil, not criminal, and must be heard in state Supreme Court,
not a county court.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-09-07-00 2050 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
