<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-07 20:51 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hillary Clinton education speech marred by hecklers; PBA endorses Lazio </HEADLINE>
By VERENA DOBNIK
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) - Hillary Rodham Clinton's speech on new education
proposals ended Thursday with a nasty outburst - the epithet ''Jew
hater!'' hurled at her from the audience.
</P>
<P>
   ''Hillary hates Israel!'' screamed two lone ultra-Orthodox
Jewish youths as she wound up her appearance before students at
Queens College.
</P>
<P>
   ''Out smut!'' yelled back a student.
</P>
<P>
   The first lady's Secret Service agents rushed out the two
members of Kahane Chai, a militant Jewish group. Clinton proceeded
with a question-and-answer session during which she outlined her
views on the Middle East.
</P>
<P>
   ''Having a Palestinian state would make sense,'' she said,
reiterating a position she first took two years ago. However, she
insisted, such a step could only come as part of a comprehensive
Middle East peace accord, not as a sudden ''unilateral move'' by
the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
   It was not quite the subject the U.S. Senate candidate, joined
by daughter Chelsea, had prepared for her speech to hundreds of
students.
</P>
<P>
   With New York public schools opening this week, Clinton had come
to outline three new proposals for better learning, noting that in
America's booming economy, ''education is the fault line between
those who will move ahead and those who are left behind.''
</P>
<P>
   If elected senator, she said she would try to fill that gap -
widened in New York by overcrowded classrooms, often poorly trained
teachers, a large turnover among principals and safety problems.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, her Senate rival, Republican Rep. Rick Lazio, was at
City Hall, picking up an endorsement from the union that represents
27,000 city police officers.
</P>
<P>
   Patrolmen's Benevolent Association President Patrick Lynch
called Lazio a ''true friend and supporter of our cops.'' He said
the group's decision was based in part on Lazio's opposition to
appointing a federal monitor to oversee the NYPD and to the
congressman's support of the death penalty.
</P>
<P>
   ''We urge all New York City police officers and their friends
and families to help make Rick Lazio our next U.S. Senator,'' Lynch
said.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has said the decision regarding the federal monitor
should be left to the Justice Department. She also supports the
death penalty.
</P>
<P>
   Introducing her new education proposals in Queens, she said
public schools ''are local responsibilities, but they must be a
national priority.''
</P>
<P>
   In the city, she said, 163 schools are opening with temporary
administrators instead of principals.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton proposed what she called a National Principal Corps to
attract 10,000 new principals over five years, at a cost of $60
million. The federal Department of Education would provide matching
grants to school districts that offer principals professional
development.
</P>
<P>
   Also using federal matching grants, Clinton said she supports
dividing mammoth schools, especially high schools, into smaller
ones. Her third proposal would require schools, as a condition of
receiving federal money, to give parents exact information about
how many youths had brought weapons to school, the number of fights
and disruptions in classrooms and violence toward teachers.
</P>
<P>
   If elected, Clinton said she also would support adding 100,000
well-qualified new teachers across the nation, offering them
financial incentives for good work and extra training.
</P>
<P>
   In a campaign press release, Lazio slammed Clinton's record on
education as ''disastrous,'' charging that the Arkansas education
system got worse after she headed a commission on improving it,
even as state spending on education increased.
</P>
<P>
   When Clinton finished speaking, she and Chelsea plunged into an
audience that personified the city's diversity, from young Muslim
women wearing scarves to Asian, black and white students.
</P>
<P>
   The two hecklers - Benjamin Peker, 19, a student at Brooklyn
Tech, and Jodi Posner, 21, who works for Kahane Chai - meanwhile
joined a dozen members of the group protesting in front of the
building.
</P>
<P>
   They were challenged by a Jewish student, Tim Rosen, a Queens
College political science major who told them: ''To say that
Hillary is anti-Semitic is outrageous. She has shown she is an
adamant supporter of Israel.''
</P>
<P>
   Later Thursday, after flying to Washington to join an
unsuccessful Republican-led effort to override President Clinton's
veto of a bill to abolish inheritance taxes, Lazio returned to New
York to greet commuters at the North Brewster Metro-North train
station in Putnam County.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm madly in love with him,'' swooned Southeast town clerk
Ruth Mazzei after the candidate kissed her hand. Other riders,
eager to get home, shook Lazio's hand and hurried along.
</P>
<P>
   On Long Island, Clinton was cheered by members of the Teamsters
labor union at an evening rally in Lake Success. The union endorsed
her last year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-09-07-00 2051 </TRAILER>
