<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Notes From Thursday's Baseball Games  </HEADLINE>
By The Associated PressAMERICAN LEAGUE:
Twins-Red Sox:
<TEXT>
<P>
   MINNESOTA: Minnesota beat Boston just twice in eight games this
season. ... Eric Milton lasted just 3 1-3 innings, his shortest
start since going just three innings against the Red Sox on the
Fourth of July. ... David Ortiz hit his first career grand slam and
matched a career high with four RBIs.
</P>
<P>
   BOSTON: Dante Bichette, acquired on Aug. 31 before playoff
rosters were set, hit his second homer with Boston to go with 16 in
Cincinnati. ... The Red Sox have 12 of their next 16 games against
either the Yankees, who lead the AL East, or Cleveland, which leads
the AL wild card race. ... Ramon Martinez has allowed at least one
run the first inning in 12 of 23 starts. Eight times he has allowed
multiple first-inning runs. ... Boston reliever Rich Garces left
with a right groin strain after getting two outs. He was considered
day-to-day.
Angels-Tigers:
</P>
<P>
   ANAHEIM: The Angels did not homer in the first three games of
their series in Detroit, matching their longest homerless stretch
of the season (April 15-17). ... 2B Adam Kennedy entered Thursday
needing 14 hits to become just the third Angel with at least 150
hits his rookie year. Wally Joyner had 172 in 1986 and Devon White
168 in 1987.
</P>
<P>
   DETROIT: OF Juan Gonzalez's flu is worse than originally
thought. ''He's going to go to the hospital and get it checked
out,'' manager Phil Garner said before Gonzalez missed his third
straight game Thursday. ''He's worse today.'' ... OF Juan
Encarnacion was hurting from fouling a ball off his foot Wednesday
and was out of Thursday's lineup. ... Bench coach Bob Melvin,
suffering from a viral infection in his middle ear, was released
from a Detroit hospital Thursday but is still several days away
from rejoining the team. ''He's very weak,'' Garner said. Bullpen
coach Lance Parrish is filling in for Melvin.
Devil Rays-Indians:
</P>
<P>
   TAMPA BAY: Three of the four Devil Rays on the U.S. Olympic team
played in a 11-2 exhibition win over Italy on Wednesday night in
Australia. C Pat Borders went 0-for-3, 2B Brent Abernathy went
1-for-2 and scored and LHP Bobby Seay pitched a hitless inning. RHP
Matt White is also on the team. ... OF Greg Vaughn needs five
homers to become the third player in history to hit 30 homers with
four different clubs. Teammate Fred McGriff and ex-Tampa player
Jose Canseco are the others. ... RHP Cory Lidle concluded his
three-game suspension for his part in an Aug. 29 brawl with Boston.
Manager Larry Rothschild served the second game of his three-game
suspension, and OF Gerald Williams and RHPs Dave Eiland and Tony
Fiore remained active pending appeal of their suspensions.
</P>
<P>
   CLEVELAND: Manager Charlie Manuel said RHP Charles Nagy may not
go to Triple-A Buffalo for a rehab start as planned. Nagy told
Manuel that he thought pitching a simulated game in Cleveland would
accomplish the same goal. Barring any setbacks, Nagy, who underwent
elbow surgery in May, will start Sept. 14 against the Boston Red
Sox. ... LHP Ricardo Rincon, who was on the disabled list more than
three months, has not allowed any of his 16 inherited runners to
score this season. ... RHP Danys Baez, the Cuban defector who
signed a four-year, $14.5 million contract this winter, will not be
called up by the Indians this month. Baez went 6-11 with a 4.02 ERA
at Kinston (A) and Akron (AA) this season. He's scheduled to pitch
in the Arizona Fall League.
Mariners-Blue Jays:
</P>
<P>
   SEATTLE: Rickey Henderson led off two of his previous three
games against Toronto starter Steve Trachsel with a homer.
Henderson singled in his first at-bat Friday night. ... Edgar
Martinez entered the game with 128 RBIs. That's the second-most
ever by a player 37 year old or older. Martinez is 37. ... Seattle
starter Freddy Garcia threw seven straight balls leading off the
second.
</P>
<P>
   TORONTO: Christine Cho, Miss Canada 2001, threw out the
ceremonial first pitch. ... SkyDome's roof was open for the first
time in five games. ... For the second straight season the Dunedin
Blue Jays (A ball) have reached the finals in the Florida State
League.
Yankees-Royals:
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK: LHP Randy Keisler will make his major league debut on
Sunday in Boston, facing Pete Schourek. Keisler's contract was
purchased from Triple-A Columbus on Tuesday. Keisler will take
David Cone's scheduled start in the rotation. Cone, meanwhile, said
he was feeling much less pain than he expected after separating his
left shoulder diving for a popped-up bunt on Tuesday. ... With a
makeup game against the Red Sox scheduled for Monday at Yankee
Stadium, the Yankees are scheduled to play on 31 consecutive days
to close the season. No team in major league baseball ever has
closed the regular season with games on more than 24 consecutive
days. The Yankees could play on 32 consecutive days, if a rainout
between New York and the Florida Marlins from July 15 must be made
up on Oct. 2.
</P>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY: The Royals are conducting their evaluation meetings
of their roster, something Manager Tony Muser said is filled with
''lots of arguing and differences of opinion. In my opinion, that
can be very healthy. It makes everyone think deeper.'' Muser said
he is willing to stir things up if the meetings get too placid.
''I'll ask the tough questions,'' he said. ... With Brian Meadows'
3-2 complete-game victory on Wednesday, Royals starters now have
pitched five complete games in their last 19, after only completing
three of their first 120 starts.
Rangers-White Sox:
</P>
<P>
   TEXAS: The Hall of Fame was on the phone Thursday morning,
asking for Scott Sheldon's jersey. Sheldon became only the third
player in major league history to play all nine positions in one
game Wednesday night. The jersey will be sent this weekend, and his
cap will be displayed at The Legends of the Game Baseball Museum at
The Ballpark in Arlington. Sheldon is getting the lineup card and a
game ball. ... Though Texas manager Johnny Oates originally planned
to have Sheldon play nine at home, he doesn't regret doing it on
the road. In fact, it probably worked out better because Sheldon's
parents, who live in Croatia, were in Chicago for this series.
''His parents, his wife and his son, they probably care more than
all the other people together,'' Oates said. ''Those are the people
that really matter. I don't have any regrets.'' ... With RHP Rick
Helling struggling, Oates has decided to give him some extra rest.
Helling had his shortest start of his career Wednesday night,
giving up seven runs in just two-thirds of an inning. ''We'll just
give him an extra day the next two starts and then see where we are
after that,'' Oates said.
</P>
<P>
   CHICAGO: With a big series against Cleveland looming this
weekend, Frank Thomas loosened the young White Sox up Wednesday
night with a two-run homer in the first inning. ''He was pretty
fired up after the home run,'' White Sox manager Jerry Manuel said.
''Frank is kind of sensing what's going on. He realizes this is big
not only for the team, but for him as well. It's a different Frank
than in year's past. He's put up great numbers (in the past). This
is great numbers and winning.'' ... This is the last time the
Rangers play the White Sox this season, so Oates made sure he
talked with Manuel before Thursday's game. ''I just congratulated
him on the year and told him to enjoy the journey,'' Oates said.
''You're not going to have this year every year.'' ... Manuel was
looking for another good outing from LHP Jim Parque, who won for
the first time since Aug. 16 on Saturday, his last start. ''We have
confidence in who we put out there. We just don't know what we're
going to get,'' Manuel said. ''If he comes up with a good outing,
we'll feel pretty good about our rotation the rest of the year.''
NATIONAL LEAGUE:
Expos-Cardinals:
</P>
<P>
   MONTREAL: Trey Moore starts Friday for the Expos as they begin a
three-game series at Atlanta. The Expos are 4-2 against the NL
West-leading Braves. ... The Expos have had 48 pitchers, tying a
franchise record set in 1993. They've used 26 pitchers, two more
than the old record set in 1990. ... Wilton Guerrero struck out all
four at-bats Thursday. ... 2B Jose Vidro will have an MRI Friday
for a sprained left elbow. ''I had a tough time swinging the bat,
so I decided not to take a chance,'' Vidro said.
</P>
<P>
   ST. LOUIS: The Cardinals are 31-25 without Mark McGwire, who has
been on the DL since July 7 with tendinitis in his right knee.
McGwire had hoped to make a pinch-hit appearance during the
just-completed seven-game homestand but is experiencing pain
breaking out of the batter's box. ''He works out hard, he gets
really sore,'' manager Tony La Russa said. ''He was really sore
today. That's why he made the comment that he didn't know if he was
going to be able to play the field.'' ... SS Edgar Renteria's
fielding error in the ninth inning Wednesday was the Cardinals'
first in 88 innings. ... Rookie Rick Ankiel, who starts Friday at
Milwaukee, has won only two of his last 13 starts. But the
Cardinals have won his last six outings. ... Darryl Kile's
10-strikeout performance was his first time in double digits since
July 2, when he also fanned 10. ... Kile gets the lowest support
among Cardinals starters, 4.7 runs per game. Pat Hentgen gets the
best support at 6.2 runs. ... The actual attendance of 23,094 was
the smallest crowd of the year.
Marlins-Astros:
</P>
<P>
   FLORIDA: Marlins manager John Boles missed his second straight
game as he has gone to Chicago to be with his ailing father. Team
officials said they didn't expect him back before the weekend.
Third base coach Fredi Gonzalez will manage the team in Boles'
absence.
</P>
<P>
   HOUSTON: Moises Alou was held out of the lineup Thursday to give
him a rest. Alou, who is second in the National League in hitting
at .359, might end up needing the plate appearances at the end of
the season if he is to compete for the batting title. Players must
have 502 appearances and with 23 games left Alou has 438. ''I was
tired,'' Alou said. ''That (the batting title) isn't something I'm
worried about.''
Diamondbacks-Braves:
</P>
<P>
   ARIZONA: The Diamondbacks have lost four of their last five
series after dropping the first two games in Atlanta. ... After
making only four errors in a 16-game stretch from Aug. 15-Sept. 2,
Arizona had six errors in the last three games. ... The
pinch-hitters have picked it up against after an 0-for-19 slump.
They came into Thursday's game riding a 7-of-21 hot streak, even
though they were hitless in their first three at-bats against the
Braves.
</P>
<P>
   ATLANTA: Reliever Kerry Ligtenberg received his degree in
chemical engineering from the University of Minnesota. He had been
one credit short but a change from quarters to semesters resulted
in his complying with the degree requirements at age 29. ''It took
me a while, but I'm happy and glad I finally got it,'' Ligtenberg
said. ''It's kind of a relief.'' He has no plans to change his
career path but added, ''Now I can say I went to college and got a
degree instead of saying I was one class short of a degree.'' ...
Outfielder B.J. Surhoff left the game in the first inning with a
pulled right quadriceps muscle. He was injured as he rounded first
following a single up the middle. Surhoff remained at the bag for
one pitch, then was replaced by George Lombard.
Padres-Giants:
</P>
<P>
   SAN DIEGO: OF Tony Gwynn acknowledged the possibility this could
be his last season. The Padres have until Nov. 1 to pick up Gwynn's
$6 million contract for 2001 or give him a $2 million buyout. ''It
might be a moot point,'' said Gwynn. ''I might have to retire. If I
don't get healthy, I can't play.'' Gwynn hasn't played since June
23. He wanted to come back from knee surgery this season, but that
appears unlikely. ''I can still swing, but how do I move?'' he
asked. ... 3B Phil Nevin, who left Wednesday's game with a strained
abdominal muscle, is doubtful for the series in San Francisco.
''It's going to be a little while,'' said Nevin.
</P>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO: Giants manager Dusty Baker is worried about the
Padres. They're only four games under .500 and are on a three-game
winning streak entering play on Thursday. ''It's always dangerous
when you're facing guys you don't know much about,'' said Baker.
''Any team which gets a well-pitched game can beat you, and they've
played us tough so far.'' Another reason Baker is worried is that
Thursday starts a span of seven games in the next 11 days against
San Diego. ''That's a third of the season left against one team,''
said Baker. ... Baker said he's going to try to give 2B Jeff Kent,
OF Barry Bonds and OF Ellis Burks a day off during the series.
''That has nothing to do with the opponent,'' said Baker. ''It has
to do with playing 20 consecutive days. That's a lot. We're trying
to keep everybody fresh and healthy and keep the bench sharp.'' ...
RHP Livan Hernandez will be going for his 12th home victory of the
season on Friday. Mike Krukow, currently a Giants broadcaster, was
the last San Francisco (1986) to win 12 games at home.
</P>
</TEXT>
