<BODY>
<HEADLINE> State takes man to court for feeding deer  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   OLD FORGE, N.Y. (AP) - Andy Bozek is in trouble with the law for
the second time since he turned 80.
</P>
<P>
   His crime? Feeding the deer.
</P>
<P>
   Bozek is 82. He and his wife Agnes live at the end of a dead end
road in Herkimer County, about 75 miles northeast of Syracuse. For
the past 45 years, feeding the deer has been a family joy.
</P>
<P>
   The state Department of Environmental Conservation, though, sees
deer feeding as a hazard to motorists and to deer who become too
reliant on humans for survival.
</P>
<P>
   So, Bozek has been ticketed twice for feeding deer within 300
feet of a highway or public road.
</P>
<P>
   At his first court hearing Thursday, supporters held signs like
''Andy loves the deer and we love Andy,'' and ''DEC, please use
some common sense.''
</P>
<P>
   ''I could see if he was living on a main highway,'' said Stella
Lopata. ''(Feeding deer) is a lot better life than sitting in a bar
room.''
</P>
<P>
   Bozek's lawyer says the 1997 law is meant to keep busy roads
safe from deer-car collisions, not rural dead-ends like Bozek's.
Bozek pleaded innocent Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm a bit nervous,'' Bozek said. ''I'm confident it will work
out in the end.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
