<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-07 21:07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ex-Ball State Player Heads To Prison  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   MUNCIE, Ind. (AP) -- A former Ball State basketball player was
sentenced Thursday to 1&AMP;frac12; years in prison after having pleaded
guilty to drug charges earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
   Jerome Davis, 22, was arrested last September after he sold 2
pounds of marijuana to a police informant. The informant was
wearing a hidden recording device when he went to Davis' apartment
and paid him $1,800 in marked bills.
</P>
<P>
   Davis, of Cleveland, was dismissed from the basketball team the
day of his arrest. He pleaded guilty in July to possession of
marijuana and maintaining a common nuisance, both felonies carrying
standard 1&AMP;frac12;-year prison terms.
</P>
<P>
   In court Thursday, Davis asked for a suspended sentence so he
could continue his studies -- and his collegiate basketball career --
at Slippery Rock University in Pennsylvania.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm no longer a boy,'' Davis told Delaware Circuit Judge
Steven Caldemeyer. ''I'm a man now. My life is headed in the right
direction.''
</P>
<P>
   According to court documents, police learned Davis was selling
marijuana after he was robbed in May 1999. Officers at that time
warned Davis, but did not arrest him.
</P>
<P>
   Caldemeyer said he found it ''particularly disturbing'' that
Davis ignored that warning and continued to sell the drug.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
