<HEADLINE> Angels 6, Tigers 4  </HEADLINE>
By LARRY LAGE
<TEXT>
<P>
   DETROIT (AP) -- Troy Glaus, Scott Spiezio and Tim Salmon homered
and Tim Belcher won the matchup of pitchers coming off the disabled
list as the Anaheim Angels beat the Detroit Tigers 6-4 Thursday
night.
</P>
<P>
   Belcher (3-2), who entered the game with a 9.69 ERA, made his
first start since July 2. He had been sidelined by a strained right
flexor muscle.
</P>
<P>
   Belcher, who pitched for the Tigers in 1994, went six innings
and gave up three runs on seven hits.
</P>
<P>
   Dave Mlicki (4-11) gave up five runs on five hits in just three
innings. Out because of a sinus infection, he made his first start
since July 22.
</P>
<P>
   Shigetoshi Hasegawa pitched the ninth for his ninth save.
</P>
<P>
   Bengie Molina went 4-for-4 as the Angels concluded their
seven-game road trip with two wins. The Tigers lost consecutive
games for the first time since Aug. 6-7.
</P>
<P>
   Glaus gave Anaheim a 1-0 lead in the second with his 41st homer,
a 422-foot drive to left field.
</P>
<P>
   The Tigers tied it in the home half on Damion Easley's RBI
single after Tony Clark doubled and Deivi Cruz singled.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels went ahead 2-1 in the third when Darin Erstad's
sacrifice fly scored Molina, who hit a leadoff double. They took a
3-1 lead on Scott Spiezio's 15th homer to right field.
</P>
<P>
   Willie Blair relieved Mlicki, who loaded the bases with no outs
in the fourth. Blair forced Adam Kennedy into a home-to-first
double play.
</P>
<P>
   Molina, the second batter Mlicki faced, hit a two-run single to
right.
</P>
<P>
   Detroit cut its deficit to 5-3 in the fifth. Brad Ausmus hit a
leadoff single and scored from first when Wendell Magee hit a
double to left-center. Billy McMillon's sacrifice fly scored Magee.
</P>
<P>
   Magee hit his sixth homer to make it 5-4 in the seventh. Salmon
gave the Angels a 6-4 cushion in the eighth with his 33rd home run.
Notes: The Angels hadn't homered in their past three games. ... Mo
Vaughn was 2-for-16 with nine strikeouts in the series. ... Glaus
committed his 28th error when he dropped McMillon's foul popup in
the eighth.
</P>
</TEXT>
