<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Buffalo Teachers Go On Strike  </HEADLINE>
By CAROLYN THOMPSON
<TEXT>
<P>
   BUFFALO, N.Y. (AP) -- Buffalo's teachers went on strike Thursday
in defiance of state law, forcing the cancellation of what would
have been the second day of school for 47,000 students.
</P>
<P>
   The walkout by the 3,800 teachers caught many people off guard.
</P>
<P>
   Parents who took their youngsters to school only to find picket
lines brought their children back home or scrambled to find someone
to watch them. YMCA and YWCA sites opened their day care centers to
non-members.
</P>
<P>
   Superintendent Marion Canedo canceled classes for Friday, saying
she had not heard anything from the union and wanted to give
parents as much time as possible to prepare for another day without
school.
</P>
<P>
   State law prohibits teachers from striking, and they stand to
lose two days pay for each day on strike. They could be jailed for
defying a court injunction obtained by the Board of Education this
week forbidding the walkout. A hearing on the injunction is set for
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Mayor Anthony Masiello called the walkout ''an unconscionable
act.''
</P>
<P>
   ''It's very punitive and very damaging to the children and the
families and it's totally uncalled for,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're all very sad. We're sad for us and sad for the
children,'' said reading teacher Sue Webster as she picketed
outside a school. ''There's not one of us that's happy to be here.
We'd all much rather be inside.''
</P>
<P>
   The union and the school system were at odds over wages, health
care and a provision to contract with social agencies outside the
district to serve troubled students. Negotiators were set to resume
Thursday evening.
</P>
<P>
   ''I am highly upset,'' said Sophia Gonzalez, 16, as she headed
home from Grover Cleveland High School. ''They said it was a new
school year and our grades were going to go up. We can't do it if
we're sitting at home.''
</P>
<P>
   Elsewhere around the country, hundreds of non-teaching employees
at the University of Texas at Austin began a three-day sickout to
protest working conditions, and a faculty strike at Eastern
Michigan University in Ypsilanti entered its third day.
</P>
<P>
   In Philadelphia, school opened for the year on time Thursday
despite a strike threat by teachers. Contract talks continued, and
both sides reported progress.
</P>
<P>
   The union representing 687 Eastern Michigan professors went on
strike Tuesday morning in the first faculty walkout at the school
since 1978. The fall semester began last week and the university
remains open, but many classes have been canceled.
</P>
<P>
   At the University of Texas, the non-teaching employees are
seeking pay raises and a rollback of increases in their insurance
premiums. A school official said the university was operating
normally despite the walkout.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   Buffalo school district: http://www.buffaloschools.org
</P>
<P>
   Eastern Michigan University: http://www.emich.edu
</P>
<P>
   American Association of University Professors:
http://www.aaup.org
</P>
<P>
   Philadelphia school district: http://www.phila.k12.pa.us
</P>
<P>
   Philadelphia teachers union: http://www.pft.org
</P>
<P>
   University of Texas at Austin: http://www.utexas.edu
</P>
</TEXT>
