<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mexican Deputy Minister Found Dead  </HEADLINE>
By TRACI CARL
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY (AP) -- A top Commerce Ministry official upset about
scandals surrounding a program he helped start was found dead along
a highway outside Mexico City, and his death was being treated as a
suicide, officials said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The body of Deputy Minister Raul Ramos Tercero was found late
Wednesday outside his car with the neck slashed, said Eliseo Lugo,
a spokesman for the attorney general's office.
</P>
<P>
   Lugo said six letters were found inside Ramos' car, including
ones to his wife, his parents, a senator, the Reforma newspaper and
two top officials at the Commerce Ministry.
</P>
<P>
   The letters said Ramos took his life because he was upset about
the controversy surrounding Mexico's National Registry of Motor
Vehicles, or Renave, Mexican State Attorney General Gerardo Sanchez
said.
</P>
<P>
   Renave has been criticized for charging too much to register
cars and corruption.
</P>
<P>
   In a separate scandal, Renave's former director, Ricardo Miguel
Cavallo, last month was implicated in Argentina's so-called ''dirty
war'' against dissidents in the 1970s and early 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   Cavallo was arrested Aug. 24 in Mexico. He is wanted by criminal
judges in Spain, France and Italy for alleged human rights abuses
in Argentina. He allegedly later fled Argentina to Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   ''The attorney general's office is certain that this was a
suicide,'' Sanchez said.
</P>
<P>
   As deputy minister of regulations and industrial services, Ramos
oversaw the creation of Renave, a government program whose services
were later contracted out to a private company.
</P>
<P>
   ''I am clean,'' he said in letters to his wife and parents,
according to Mexico's federal attorney general's office. ''I'm a
good man, and I always have been. In carrying out my official
responsibilities, I have never benefitted from my position in an
illicit way. My life is an open book in that there is nothing to
expose.''
</P>
<P>
   Ramos, an economist who attended the Autonomous Technological
Institute of Mexico and Stanford University, began his career with
the Bank of Mexico and later participated in negotiations of the
North American Free Trade Agreement.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
