<HEADLINE> White Sox 10, Rangers 6  </HEADLINE>
By NANCY ARMOUR
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO (AP) -- Magglio Ordonez hit a go-ahead, two-run homer in
the sixth inning and then added an insurance shot in the eighth as
the Chicago White Sox rallied for a 10-6 victory over the Texas
Rangers on Thursday night.
</P>
<P>
   It was the fifth career multihomer game for Ordonez and third
this season.
</P>
<P>
   Carlos Lee added a solo shot and Frank Thomas drove in three
runs for the White Sox, who came back from a 4-0 deficit.
</P>
<P>
   Lorenzo Barcelo (3-1) gave up one run and two hits in 2 1-3
innings. Keith Foulke got the last five outs for his 28th save in
33 chances.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Zimmerman (3-5) only gave up one run in two innings, but it
was Ordonez's homer.
</P>
<P>
   One night after becoming only the third player in major league
history to play all nine spots in a game, Scott Sheldon stayed put
for Texas. He made his 10th start of the year at third base.
</P>
<P>
   With Cleveland losing, the White Sox extended their lead in the
AL Central to 7&AMP;frac12; games. Chicago heads to Cleveland on Friday for a
series at Jacobs Field.
</P>
<P>
   Texas starter Kenny Rogers had lost his last two starts, but he
looked sharp early against the White Sox. He retired the first 12
batters he faced, striking out three of them.
</P>
<P>
   Ricky Ledee homered as Texas took a 4-0 lead, and Rogers looked
as if he might get his first victory since Aug. 8.
</P>
<P>
   But Lee singled with one out in the fifth, and things went
downhill pretty quickly after that. After another single by Paul
Konerko, Herbert Perry hit a sacrifice fly to cut the Rangers' lead
to 4-1.
</P>
<P>
   Rogers started the sixth with his first walk of the night, to
Charles Johnson, and plunked Ray Durham. Tony Graffanino hit an RBI
single to center, giving the White Sox runners at the corners with
no outs and Thomas up to bat.
</P>
<P>
   The fans started chanting ''M-V-P! M-V-P!'' as Thomas stepped to
the plate, and he didn't disappoint. His double to deep center
field almost lodged in the bullpen fence. By the time Ledee got it
back to the infield, Durham and Graffanino had scored and Thomas
was standing at second, clapping his hands.
</P>
<P>
   That was it for Rogers, who was relieved by Zimmerman. He didn't
fare any better, though, as Ordonez sent the first pitch he saw
over the fence in right field to give the White Sox a 6-5 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Ordonez homered off Darwin Cubillan to start the eighth. Lee
followed with another solo home run, Durham had a sacrifice fly and
Thomas had an RBI single as the White Sox added four more runs.
</P>
<P>
   Luis Alicea and Chad Curtis hit RBI singles as the Rangers took
a 4-0 lead. The Rangers made it 5-1 in the sixth on an RBI single
by Bill Haselman.
</P>
<P>
Notes: The White Sox have hit back-to-back homers 16 times this
season. ... The White Sox presented Jose Valentin and Chris
Singleton with ''Hit for the Cycle'' rings before the game. The
14-karat gold rings have an onyx stone with a white enamel overlay
in the shape of the infield. Four small diamonds represent the four
bases. Valentin hit for the cycle April 27 against Baltimore.
Singleton did it July 6, 1999.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
