<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-07 23:06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jet, Air Force Craft in Near-Miss  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES (AP) -- An F-117 stealth fighter flew close enough to
a United Airlines jet to set off the passenger plane's on-board
radar Thursday, the airline and the military said.
</P>
<P>
   The incident occurred shortly after United flight 174 left Los
Angeles International Airport for Boston about 8:30 a.m., said
Chris Nardella, a spokeswoman for United, which is based in the
Chicago suburb of Elk Grove Village.
</P>
<P>
   The Boeing 757 was flying at about 10,800 feet when its on-board
radar equipment detected an approaching aircraft. Nardella said the
crew kept the plane at that altitude until the Air Force jet passed
overhead.
</P>
<P>
   Preliminary reports showed the United plane and an F-117
Nighthawk stealth fighter came within 500 feet vertically and
six-tenths of a mile horizontally of each other, FAA spokesman
Jerry Snyder said Thursday night.
</P>
<P>
   According to Visual Flight Rules, which the Nighthawk flies by,
''this 500 feet separation was within safe perimeters for all
passing aircrafts,'' Snyder said.
</P>
<P>
   The stealth jet, which is able to evade radar, was broadcasting
its position publicly when the near-miss occurred.
</P>
<P>
   ''The F-117, on a training flight, was not in stealth
configuration and was flying according to FAA rules,'' the Air
Force said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   Under such conditions the plane uses a standard transponder to
alert other aircraft to its position, the Air Force said.
</P>
<P>
   The F-117 flies out of an Air Force facility in Palmdale, about
60 miles from Los Angeles, and the squadron is based at Edwards Air
Force Base.
</P>
<P>
   The United flight carried 166 passengers and seven crew.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-09-07-00 2306 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000907.0199 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-07 23:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 15 Counties, Cities in Census Case  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- A federal court has allowed 15 cities and
counties from around the country to join a court battle over a
Virginia law requiring the use of an exact numerical count when it
redraws political districts.
</P>
<P>
   The Virginia Legislature passed the law this year that prohibits
the use of statistical sampling when the state redraws its
political districts to reflect the 2000 census.
</P>
<P>
   The Census Bureau plans to release two sets of population
counts: a raw head count on Dec. 31 and the sampled count by April
1.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats say sampling helps account for minorities, the
homeless and others who have been undercounted in the past.
Republicans generally favor an exact count.
</P>
<P>
   Virginia, because of its history of racial discrimination, is
one of 16 states required under the federal Voting Rights Act to
gain Justice Department approval to change certain voting laws. In
April, the state asked a three-judge panel of U.S. District Court
for the District of Columbia to rule that the law prohibiting
sampling is acceptable.
</P>
<P>
   The case is being closely watched by other states with similar
laws.
</P>
<P>
   In a Sept. 1 order, the judges granted a bid by the localities
to join the lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   A court hearing is scheduled for Sept. 21. The Justice
Department has asked the judges to dismiss the case.
</P>
<P>
   The 15 cities, led by Los Angeles, sought to intervene in the
case, arguing that Virginia's plan would be harmful to urban areas
that need sampling to fully account for their population and
receive their full share of federal dollars.
</P>
<P>
   Others involved include Richmond, Va.; Houston; Denver and San
Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   The Supreme Court ruled last year that the raw count must be
used when reapportioning House seats among states. It left open to
states the option to use sampled data when redrawing political
district lines.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-09-07-00 2311 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000907.0200 </DOCNO>
