<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-07 23:41 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Argentina Votes To Lift Immunity  </HEADLINE>
By LAURENCE NORMAN
<TEXT>
<P>
   BUENOS AIRES, Argentina (AP) -- Argentina's lower house approved
a bill Thursday that would limit the immunity of lawmakers from
prosecution in a move that could strengthen an investigation into
alleged vote-buying in the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   The House of Deputies voted 205 to 5 in favor of the bill, which
states that while lawmakers have immunity from arrest, they do not
have immunity from judicial investigations into wrongdoing.
</P>
<P>
   To become law, the bill must be approved by the Senate and
signed by President Fernando De la Rua.
</P>
<P>
   But the Senate on Wednesday, in its first session since the
scandal broke, refused to address the immunity issue, partly
because the two main legislative party blocs could not reach
agreement on how to address the crisis.
</P>
<P>
   The bill means, among other things, that 11 senators implicated
in the vote-buying scandal would lose their immunity.
</P>
<P>
   The senators are alleged to have accepted bribes in exchange for
voting for a controversial labor reform bill in May.
</P>
<P>
   The claims of bribe-taking, which have yet to be substantiated,
have touched off a media frenzy in Argentina, amid speculation that
up to $200,000 had been paid out to sway passage of the labor bill.
</P>
<P>
   The bill, considered a centerpiece of De la Rua's efforts to
revive Argentina's faltering economy, won overwhelming approval in
both congressional houses.
</P>
<P>
   The accusations of vote buying have already affected the
popularity of De la Rua's nine-month-old administration, which took
office for a four-year term on promises to stamp out corruption and
provide honest government.
</P>
<P>
   Federal Judge Carlos Liporaci has said 11 senators should be
stripped of their immunity. If not, he said, ''the investigation
will inevitably be limited.''
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, Interior Minister Federico Storani said that it is
''likely'' that the President Fernando De la Rua would respond to
the scandal by reshuffling his cabinet when he returns Sept. 15
from a trip abroad.
</P>
<P>
   Storani did not say what the changes would be.
</P>
<P>
   ''We believe that changes in the Senate should be mirrored by
changes within the executive branch because this current political
crisis is very deep,'' Storani told a local radio station.
</P>
<P>
   However, De la Rua said while visiting New York on Thursday for
the U.N. Milennium study that he did not anticipate making any
cabinet changes.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't want it said that I will make changes when I come
back. I am not anticipating any such Cabinet crisis,'' he was
quoted by the Argentine news agency Diarios y Noticias.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-09-07-00 2341 </TRAILER>
