<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Khatami Seeks Apology From U.S.  </HEADLINE>
By SAM F. GHATTAS
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Iran's president said Thursday that relations
between his country and the United States will improve only if the
Americans apologize for past policies in Iran -- and even that may
not be enough.
</P>
<P>
   There are ''the various sanctions. There are animosities, there
are allegations against Iran,'' said Mohammad Khatami, at a news
conference. ''We need apology for those as well as some practical
measures and steps that prove that in reality the behavior has
changed.
</P>
<P>
   ''But unfortunately, in practice, Americans have been less
inclined to do this,'' said Khatami, one of about 150 leaders
attending the three-day Millennium Summit at the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton also is in New York and on Wednesday the
leaders listened to each other's speeches at the U.N. General
Assembly. But Khatami was not invited to a reception hosted by
Clinton Thursday night at New York's Metropolitan Museum, said
National Security Council spokesman P.J. Crowley. Iraq, Libya and
Cuba were also excluded.
</P>
<P>
   The mere presence of both presidents at the United Nations
sparked the possibility of an encounter, even by coincidence.
</P>
<P>
   But Khatami indicated that any such meeting would be premature,
because Iran still had ''serious issues'' with the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Khatami, the reform-minded cleric who has been seeking better
relations with the West since his election in 1997, has taken steps
to open up Iran and improve its international standing by calling
for dialogue between the Americans and the Iranians.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration has addressed Iranian grievances and
also has taken some concrete steps in the area of trade and
people-to-people contact. In February, Secretary of State Madeleine
Albright said Iranians have reason to resent the American
intervention in the 1953 coup on behalf of Shah Mohammad Reza
Pahlavi, but she did not apologize.
</P>
<P>
   Albright also lifted sanctions on some Iranian imports,
including the famed Persian carpets, and announced a reduction in
restrictions to contacts between American and Iranian scholars,
artists and athletes.
</P>
<P>
   But Khatami, who is locked in a power struggle at home with
hardliners who oppose reforms and his opening up to the West, said
that American gestures were not adequate.
</P>
<P>
   Khatami said the United States must acknowledge and apologize
for past wrong policies, including the 1953 coup and what he
described as damage done to his nation by U.S.-backed regimes since
then.
</P>
<P>
   ''The Americans will have to confess to this. Through this
confession -- if the Americans accept to do it -- I think it will be
a very big step toward removing our misunderstandings. But
unfortunately, in action, they have not done this,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Khatami said the controversy over 10 Iranian Jews convicted for
espionage on behalf of Israel in Iran was blown out of proportion.
He said the government would not interfere in the case, which has
drawn condemnation from Israel and criticism from the United States
</P>
<P>
   ''If instead of these Jews they were Christians, would the world
still react as it does today?'' he asked.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-09-07-00 2343 </TRAILER>
