<DOCNO> APW20000907.0209 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-07 23:48 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tampa Bay's Rupe Still Hospitalized  </HEADLINE>
By TOM WITHERS
<TEXT>
<P>
   CLEVELAND (AP) -- Tampa Bay pitcher Ryan Rupe remained
hospitalized Thursday after a blood clot was discovered above his
right biceps, and he underwent a procedure to have an arm vein
opened to improve blood flow.
</P>
<P>
   The 25-year-old Rupe left his start Wednesday night against the
Indians in the third inning complaining of stiffness in his arm.
But after being examined by Devil Rays trainer Jamie Reed and
Cleveland team doctor Louis Keppler, Rupe was taken to the
hospital.
</P>
<P>
   ''He came out after the first inning and said his arm was a
little stiff,'' Reed said. ''But that's him, he's a battler. He
didn't want to come out.''
</P>
<P>
   But Reed said he knew something was more drastically wrong with
Rupe, who in 1997 had surgery to remove part of a rib in his right
arm pit and has had previous circulation problems.
</P>
<P>
   ''His hand was really swollen and the vein through his biceps
looked like a garden hose it was so engorged,'' said Reed. ''This
was abnormal.''
</P>
<P>
   When Rupe got the hospital doctors discovered a blockage in his
biceps and a blood clot in his upper arm, Reed said. It is not
uncommon for patients who have surgeries similar to the one Rupe
underwent in '97 to develop blood clots.
</P>
<P>
   ''But this was beyond his normal,'' Reed said.
</P>
<P>
   Rupe was given a blood thinning medication to dissolve the blood
clot. He had one of the two veins that return blood from his hand
to his heart cleared on Thursday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   ''The procedure was very successful,'' Tampa Bay manager Larry
Rothschild said. ''He'll be monitored over the next 24-48 hours and
will probably be released in Saturday.''
</P>
<P>
   After his release, Rupe will return to St. Petersburg, Fla., and
will be examined by Devil Rays vascular specialist Dr. Larry
Williams.
</P>
<P>
   Barring any complications, Rupe may be able to start doing light
exercise as early as next week. Reed said it was too early to say
whether or not Rupe would pitch again this season.
</P>
<P>
   But Rothschild suggested it might be better for Rupe to wait
until next spring before he returns.
</P>
<P>
   ''I would question whether he'll be able to come back this
year,'' Rothschild said.
</P>
<P>
   Rothschild praised Reed for his role in diagnosing Rupe's
condition, which could have been life-threatening had it not been
caught.
</P>
<P>
   ''For an injury that's not very common, he did a heck of a
job,'' said Rothschild. ''Jamie is the one who noticed it. I give
him credit because you never know what can happen with those
things.''
</P>
<P>
   Rupe was selected in the sixth round of the 1998 draft by the
Devils Rays. Last season he became the first Tampa draft pick to be
called up and went 8-9 with a 4.55 ERA in 24 starts.
</P>
<P>
   He was 5-6 with a 6.92 ERA in 18 starts this season.
</P>
<P>
   Following Tampa Bay's 4-3 win Thursday night, Rothschild said he
was relieved to hear Rupe was doing fine.
</P>
<P>
   ''That was very good news,'' he said. ''We really didn't know
how serious it was, so nobody on the team was really scared. From
what they told me, it was not life-threatening. If it was in the
lower extremities, that would have been a lot worse.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-09-07-00 2348 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000907.0210 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-07 23:49 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indians Ready for Shot With Sox  </HEADLINE>
By TOM WITHERS
<TEXT>
<P>
   CLEVELAND (AP) -- They've stalked the Chicago White Sox for a few
months. And this weekend, the Cleveland Indians finally have a
chance to shake them.
</P>
<P>
   ''There's no question we've been basically dying to face Chicago
again,'' Indians reliever Paul Shuey said. ''We have one more shot
at a team that's been kicking our butts all year.''
</P>
<P>
   The Indians will open a three-game series on Friday night
against the AL Central-leading White Sox, who insist they're not
feeling any pressure at all.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think it's bigger for them,'' said Frank Thomas. ''They want
to make a statement. We've pretty much led the division all year,
and they've controlled the division the last six, seven years. They
still feel they can win it, so we've got to go in and play our
butts off and show them we're for real.''
</P>
<P>
   After blowing a 3-0 lead Thursday night and losing 4-3 to Tampa
Bay, Cleveland leads the AL wild card race by two games but trails
the White Sox by 7&AMP;frac12; games in the division. It's the same deficit
the Indians faced on June 21 -- the last time they played the White
Sox.
</P>
<P>
   But the Indians are a far different team than they were in June.
</P>
<P>
   And so are the White Sox, who are 7-3 against Cleveland this
season and swept a three-game series at Jacobs Field in June.
</P>
<P>
   ''That's true, but half that team wasn't there,'' Thomas said.
''They're a tough, tough ballclub when they're rolling. They're
going to be on their 'A' game because they're already on it.
They've been waiting for us to roll in.''
</P>
<P>
   Cleveland, which couldn't shake the injury bug for the first few
months this season, has gone 23-11 since Aug. 2, trimming four
games off Chicago's seemingly insurmountable divisional lead.
</P>
<P>
   But although his team has been playing better for more than a
month, Cleveland manager Charlie Manuel began noticing a drastic
change in his players following a 10-9 loss at Anaheim on Aug. 27.
</P>
<P>
   In that game, the Indians blew a 3-0 lead and had three runners
thrown out at the plate.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think that's when we really started playing better,'' Manuel
said. ''Our players made up their minds that we wanted to play
better and they've raised up their intensity. They seemed to get
mad, and I didn't have to say a thing.''
</P>
<P>
   In their next 10 games, the Indians went 8-2.
</P>
<P>
   There have been other changes in the Indians since the last time
they saw the White Sox. Through trades Cleveland added David Segui
and Wil Cordero to its lineup and Steve Woodard, Bob Wickman and
Jason Bere to the pitching staff.
</P>
<P>
   Those e additions have helped resurrect a season which seemed
doomed by injuries early on.
</P>
<P>
   ''With all that has happened to us, just getting to the
postseason would be special,'' said Indians general manager John
Hart said. ''We've gotten healthy. We've made trades and we've
played well in August and so far in September.''
</P>
<P>
   Extending their season beyond Oct. 1 won't be easy for the
Indians. Beginning Friday, Cleveland will play 18 of its final 25
games against playoff contenders, including eight against the
Boston Red Sox -- their closest wild-card pursuer.
</P>
<P>
   Winning their sixth straight division title isn't out of the
question, but the Indians know time is running out.
</P>
<P>
   And this weekend the Indians can close the gap on Chicago
without having to rely on any outside help.
</P>
<P>
   ''This series is meaningful,'' Hart said. ''I don't think
sending a message to the White Sox is necessarily what we're out to
do.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-09-07-00 2349 </TRAILER>
