<DOCNO> APW20000907.0213 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-07 23:55 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hamilton Township teachers vote to defy judge's order  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   HAMILTON, N.J. (AP) - Despite the threat of being fined, fired
or even sent to jail, striking teachers in the Hamilton Township
district voted unanimously Thursday to defy a state Superior Court
judge's back to work order.
</P>
<P>
   The teachers, at a dawn meeting, voted to return to picket lines
despite the possible consequences, said Karen Joseph, spokeswoman
for the New Jersey Education Association.
</P>
<P>
   ''Everyone in the room said, yes, they understood they could be
fined, they could be fired, they could be jailed, they could be
assigned community service but that's when you have to stand.
That's what you have to do,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Joseph said the teachers are willing to face the consequences
because they're frustrated. For the past 10 years, teachers have
agreed to smaller raises than they wanted, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ''Now they've reached a point where they said, 'Enough is
enough.' There is a $4.5 million surplus in the school budget.
Taxpayers have voted three years in a row to support the school
budget,'' she said. ''Life is good. These are good times and now
what's right is right and this board is not getting the message.''
</P>
<P>
   Following the union's vote, school officials canceled classes
for Thursday but remained hopeful that school would be open Friday.
''We're still taking this on a day-by-day basis,'' a district
spokeswoman said.
</P>
<P>
   Superior Court Judge Anthony J. Parrillo on Wednesday ordered
the teachers to go back to work. He also ordered both sides to hold
another negotiating session Thursday night. The session ended at
about 11:30 p.m. with the mediator ordering both sides to return to
the table at 6 p.m. on Sunday, Joseph said.
</P>
<P>
   She said the union was still on strike Thursday night and would
hold a general membership meeting at 5:30 a.m. Friday. She said the
meeting would be to update members on the situation.
</P>
<P>
   Joseph said the union believes the school should be closed
Friday, but ''that's a decision the administration makes.''
</P>
<P>
   Members of the Hamilton Township Education Association, which
represents about 1,450 teachers and other staff in the Mercer
County district, went on strike Wednesday morning.
</P>
<P>
   The union and the board of education reached an impasse in
negotiating a new, three-year contract. Salary increases and health
insurance issues remained unresolved. Union officials have
requested 5 percent raises in each of the three years of the
contract; the board has offered raises of 4 percent in the first
year of the contract, 4.1 percent in the second year and 4.2
percent in the third year.
</P>
<P>
   Courts in New Jersey have ruled that public employees do not
have the right to strike.
</P>
<P>
   The New Jersey School Boards Association has condemned the
strike and criticized the union for ''continuing to disrupt
students' education and the daily life of families in the
community.''
</P>
<P>
   ''Unfortunately the teachers union has decided to compound the
issue by violating the judge's order,'' said Mike Yaple, spokesman
for the school boards association.
</P>
<P>
   Yaple said the district could return to court to seek
enforcement of the order.
</P>
<P>
   District officials did not request that Parrillo enforce the
order Thursday, the court clerk said.
</P>
<P>
   District Superintendent Neil A. Bencivengo was meeting with
principals Thursday and was not immediately available for comment,
a receptionist said.
</P>
<P>
   Fines or other penalties would be determined by a judge, Yaple
said. Fines can be levied against union members and the union
itself.
</P>
<P>
   It is rare for striking teachers to be sentenced to jail, Yaple
said.
</P>
<P>
   ''It hasn't been done in quite a number of years,'' he said.
''In fact we as an association discourage that concept.''
</P>
<P>
   Not including the strike by teachers in Hamilton Township, there
have been eight strikes by New Jersey teachers in the past eight
years, Yaple said. They lasted an average of two to three days.
</P>
<P>
   In the five years before that, there were three times as many
strikes, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ''Substantial fines were imposed by courts since then and strike
activity decreased dramatically in the 1992-1993 school year,'' he
said. ''Fines made a difference and at the time there was a growing
lack of public support for teachers' strikes.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-09-07-00 2355 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000907.0214 </DOCNO>
