<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-07 23:57 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippines Hostages Seen Released  </HEADLINE>
By JIM GOMEZ
<TEXT>
<P>
   ZAMBOANGA, Philippines (AP) -- Mediators visited the camp of a
rebel group holding several hostages on Friday, saying later that
at least some of the group's six Europeans captives would soon be
freed.
</P>
<P>
   ''For sure, there will be a release today,'' said one of the two
go-betweens, whose code-named is ''Dragon.'' He is the uncle of one
of the Abu Sayyaf rebel commanders.
</P>
<P>
   The release, originally expected Friday morning, was delayed by
a series of last-minute snags. An official close to the negotiating
team said Libyan officials had brought only $4 million in ransom
money, enough to pay for the release of just four of the hostages.
</P>
<P>
   The Abu Sayyaf rebels had earlier pledged to free all six on
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Libya has played a prominent role in negotiations for 21 people
kidnapped April 23 from Malaysia's Sipadan diving resort. Last week
it paid $6 million for the release of six other Westerners from the
group, negotiators said. It insists the money will go for
development projects, not directly to the rebels.
</P>
<P>
   But Libya has resisted paying for two of the remaining hostages,
both French television journalists seized while covering the
hostage crisis, saying their company should foot the bill.
</P>
<P>
   Ambassadors from the hostages' countries were scheduled to fly
to the southern port city of Zamboanga later Friday to receive the
captives from negotiators. The freed hostages are to fly Saturday
to Libya on their way home.
</P>
<P>
   The rebels are still holding two Finns, a French and a German
from Sipadan and the two journalists in their camp on Jolo island,
as well as 12 Filipino Christian evangelists who were captured in
early July. A Filipino hostage from Sipadan was taken to the camp
of another rebel faction.
</P>
<P>
   A separate faction also is holding an American man, Jeffrey
Schilling, kidnapped early last week.
</P>
<P>
   The government negotiator working for Schilling's release said
emissaries have contacted rebel spokesman Abu Sabaya, who belongs
to that faction, but negotiations had not yet begun. ''As of this
moment, Abu Sabaya's group keeps on moving for security reasons,''
provincial Vice Governor Munib Estino said.
</P>
<P>
   The rebels have not announced their demands for Schilling's
release, although Sabaya has privately demanded $10 million,
negotiators said.
</P>
<P>
   Schilling, 24, a Muslim convert from Oakland, California, was
seized Aug. 28 when he visited an Abu Sayyaf camp with his Filipino
Muslim wife, Ivi Osani.
</P>
<P>
   Presidential Press Secretary Ricardo Puno said Schilling appears
to be in good condition, despite earlier reports he was ill. ''He's
not undergoing rough treatment. He's OK,'' Puno said.
</P>
<P>
   Philippine officials have questioned whether the case is a
simple kidnapping since Osani is Sabaya's second cousin and the
widow of a rebel killed by government forces. Osani was not
abducted and is being held in protective custody in a military
hospital.
</P>
<P>
   ''It could either be pure love or there could be a lot of
intrigue in the background,'' Puno said. ''At this time we cannot
say with any finality what her role was. But it certainly was not a
passive one since she made arrangements for him to go to the
camp.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-09-07-00 2357 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000907.0216 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-07 23:58 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Minn. Family Treated for Anthrax  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. PAUL, Minn. (AP) -- Six members of a Minnesota farm family
are being treated after eating meat from a cow that had anthrax,
health officials said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The Minnesota Department of Health didn't provide information on
their conditions, but said two developed symptoms of
gastrointenstinal anthrax. Anthrax usually infects the skin, but
can affect the digestive track and respiratory system.
</P>
<P>
   ''There's never been a case of gastrointestinal anthrax reported
in the United States,'' said Richard Danila, assistant state
epidemiologist. ''This was a very unique set of circumstances that
happened whereby a family of six consumed meat found to be heavily
contaminated with anthrax.''
</P>
<P>
   They raised the cow on their own farm and had it processed at a
small custom slaughterhouse. Regulators don't inspect meat in such
cases because it was for the family's own use.
</P>
<P>
   The health department said the general public isn't at risk
because animals processed for commercial sale are inspected.
</P>
<P>
   Cattle catch the disease by ingesting spores from the anthrax
bacteria, but humans rarely become infected. If inhaled, anthrax
can be deadly in humans.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   Minnesota Department of Health
http://www.health.state.mn.us/news/news.html
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-09-07-00 2358 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000907.0217 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-07 23:59 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Albright Speaks on Montenegro  </HEADLINE>
By BARRY SCHWEID
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS (AP) -- In a thinly veiled warning to Belgrade,
Secretary of State Madeleine Albright voiced concern Thursday about
the safety of Montenegro and its independence-minded President Milo
Djukanovic.
</P>
<P>
   At a news conference, Albright also disclosed plans for a joint
NATO naval exercise with Croatia off the coast of Montenegro, the
smaller of the two republics of Yugoslavia. At the Pentagon,
spokesman Kenneth Bacon said fewer than 300 Marines would take part
in a weeklong exercise later this month. He said planning for the
exercise began before the elections were called in Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   Djukanovic, a leading foe of Yugoslav President Slobodan
Milosevic, and his ruling coalition have refused to participate in
Yugoslavia's presidential election Sept. 24. He claimed recently
that if the republic of 600,000 took part, it would give legitimacy
to the Belgrade government and prolong its survival.
</P>
<P>
   Milosevic's behavior has always been ''undemocratic,''
Djukanovic said.
</P>
<P>
   Albright said the Montenegrin president ''is always in a very
difficult position.''
</P>
<P>
   ''He is someone who is taking a lot of risks for democracy in
Montenegro, and I think there is obviously concern generally for
his security,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   While denying reports that she had offered Djukanovic security
guarantees at their breakfast meeting Thursday, she said pointedly:
''We are concerned about the security of Montenegro and of
President Djukanovic, and nothing is off the table.''
</P>
<P>
   Milosevic long has been a target both of U.S. rhetoric and NATO
fire.
</P>
<P>
   Serbia, the larger of Yugoslavia's two republics, was bombed by
the U.S.-led allies to force the departure of Serb troops and
special police from Kosovo, a Serb province where they were accused
of mass slaughter of ethnic Albanians.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, the Clinton administration has provided
financial assistance to Montenegro, strengthening Djukanovic's hand
in confronting the Yugoslav president.
</P>
<P>
   Tensions have grown in Montenegro amid Djukanovic's call for a
boycott of the elections and his allegations Milosevic imposed
changes in the Yugoslav constitution to weaken Montenegro's
influence.
</P>
